# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antarctica-novel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] The novel is set in the year 2312, in the great city of Terminator on Mercury, which is built on gigantic tracks in order to constantly stay in the planet's habitable zone near the terminator.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Swan Er Hong, an artist and former asteroid terrarium designer, is grieving over the sudden death of her step-grandmother, Alex, who was very influential among the inhabitants of Terminator.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] After the funeral procession, a conference is held among the family and the close friends of Alex, some of whom Swan has never heard of.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] This includes Fitz Wahram, a native of the moon Titan, and Jean Genette, a police detective who has been exiled from Mars.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Following the conference, Swan goes to Io to deliver a message to another friend of Alex's, called Wang, who has designed one of the largest qubes, or quantum computers.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] While Swan is visiting Wang on Io, an apparent attack of some sort fails.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] An attack on Terminator shortly follows; a meteorite of artificial origin destroys the city's tracks, stopping the city and exposing it to sun, essentially cooking it.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] As Swan travels, she learns more of the mystery surrounding her grandmother's death and the destruction of her home-city of Terminator.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] With Wahram and Genette, Swan travels throughout the Solar System and investigates an escalating series of conspiracies.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] The complexity of the attack leads Genette to determine that quantum computers must have been used.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Eventually the characters learn that the attack was motivated by conflicts within the Venusian government, in the course of which a number of qubes in humanoid bodies have been secretly manufactured and sent to infiltrate human society.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] The humanoid qubes are arrested, along with a small number of humans involved in this conspiracy, and exiled on board a generation ship leaving the solar system.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Meanwhile, Swan and Wahram become involved in restoring and rewilding the climate-change-ravaged Earth by returning thousands of species from space-based habitats to their home environments on the Earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Swan and Wahram fall in love over the course of the novel, marrying at the end.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] In the world of the novel, the planets Mercury, Venus, and Mars are inhabited by humans, as are the moons of Saturn and Jupiter.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Humans have a presence (or are building one) on all the inhabitable surfaces (including moons and satellites) within the Solar System.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Almost all the Solar System's largest asteroids have been hollowed out to form "terrariums", which include an interior artificial environment designed to mimic various biomes (or combinations of these) found on earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Some terrariums serve as animal reserves or farms for endangered or under-produced flora and fauna.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Humans take shuttles to these asteroids and use them as transportation around the system.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] In the novel, scientific and technological advances—such as human enhancement, settlements on other planets, and terraforming—have opened gateways to an extraordinary future.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] A major innovation is *qubes*, which are quantum computers possessing artificial intelligence (AI), often small enough that the wearer can have one implanted into their head or attached to their body (as one might wear a watch or carry a phone).
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Digital AI is still in use, but it is being supplanted by the smaller and more powerful *qubes*.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Capitalism has generally been replaced by a planned economy that is based on the mondragon (a Spanish cooperative federation) and controlled by quantum computers, but remnants of the market system persist on Earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] As part of a process for extending the human lifespan, many people exhibit intersex or "gynandromorphous" sex characteristics, including both penises and vaginas.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Robinson has said that the novel began with the idea of a romance between two characters from Mercury and Saturn ("mercurial" and "saturnine" in temperament, respectively), with the broader setting being developed later.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] The idea of a city that slowly moves around Mercury to avoid direct light from the Sun first appeared in Robinson's earlier novel *The Memory of Whiteness*, in addition to a brief mention in his *Mars* Trilogy.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] It is also briefly mentioned in his 2015 novel *Aurora*.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] There are a number of other minor links to the *Mars* Trilogy, though it is clear that they take place in different fictional universes--e.g., Swan's AI shares the name of John Boone's AI ("Pauline").
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Critical reception for *2312* has been mixed to positive.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] Writing in *Slate*, Choire Sicha praised the book as "brilliant", while the *Guardian'*s M.
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] John Harrison criticized its ending as "contrived".
[src:antarctica-novel/2312-novel] In the *Los Angeles Times*, Jeff VanderMeer called the novel a "treasured gift to fans of passionate storytelling", writing that its "audacity" was an asset.
[src:antarctica-novel/a-short-sharp-shock] His journey takes him along the narrow strip of land, surrounded by ocean, that constitutes the entire world.
[src:antarctica-novel/a-short-sharp-shock] The phrase "short, sharp shock" is taken from the comic opera *The Mikado*, by the Victorian-era theatrical partnership Gilbert and Sullivan.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The **Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station** is a United States scientific research station at the South Pole of the Earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] It is the southernmost point under the jurisdiction (not sovereignty) of the United States.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station is located on the high plateau of Antarctica at 9,301 feet (2,835 m) above sea level.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] It is administered by the Office of Polar Programs of the National Science Foundation, specifically the United States Antarctic Program (USAP).
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] It is named in honor of Norwegian Roald Amundsen and Briton Robert F.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Scott, leaders of the competing first and second expeditions to reach the pole, in the summer of 1911–1912.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Before November 1956, there was no permanent artificial structure at the pole, and practically no human presence in the interior of Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The few scientific stations in Antarctica were near its coast.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station has been continuously occupied since it was built and has been rebuilt, expanded, and upgraded several times.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station is the only inhabited place on the surface of the Earth from which the Sun is continuously visible for six months; it is then continuously dark for the next six months, with approximately two days of averaged dark and light, twilight, namely the equinoxes.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] These are, in observational terms, called one extremely long "day" and one equally long "night".
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the six-month "day", the angle of elevation of the Sun above the horizon varies incrementally.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The Sun reaches a rising position throughout the September equinox, and then it is apparent highest at the December solstice which is summer solstice for the south, setting on the March equinox.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the six-month polar night, air temperatures can drop below −73 °C (−99 °F) and blizzards are more frequent.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Between these storms, and regardless of the weather for wavelengths unaffected by drifting snow, the roughly 5+3⁄4 months of ample darkness and dry atmosphere make the station an excellent site for astronomical observations.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The number of scientific researchers and members of the support staff housed at the Amundsen–Scott Station has always varied seasonally, with a peak population of around 150 in the summer operational season from October to February.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In recent years, the wintertime population has been around 50 people.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Supplies come seasonally, during the warm season by air or by the South Pole Traverse after it is opened; this traverse links the station to Scott Base and McMurdo Station on Ross Island since 2005 and reduces the number of flights in.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Much of the logistical support for the South Pole Station flows through McMurdo which has the farthest south port, Winter's Bay.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] For the International Geophysical Year, the United States and many other countries embarked on an international exploration of the South Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This led to the USA creating a series of stations for this project, and returning to the South Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] After a few years the Antarctic treaty was established that provided an international framework for the exploration and study of Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Navy Douglas R4D-5L named *Que Sera Sera* landed at the South Pole in Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This was the first time humans had been at the pole since 1912 (see Robert F.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] South Pole station was one of seven bases that the United States built for the International Geophysical Year, which also included McMurdo, Hallett, Wilkes, Byrd Station, Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station (South Pole Station), Ellsworth, and Little America.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Operation Deep Freeze missions support the construction and operation of the South Pole station, starting with Operation Deep Freeze 1955, and succeeded by "Operation Deep Freeze II", and so on.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In 1960, the year of the fifth mission, codenames began to be based on the year (e.g., "Operation Deep Freeze 60").
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The original South Pole station is now referred to as "Old Pole".
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Navy Seabees led by LTJG Richard Bowers, the eight-man Advance Party being transported by the VX-6 Air Squadron in two R4Ds on November 20, 1956.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Eighteenth Air Force's C-124 Globemaster IIs airdropped most of the equipment and building material.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The buildings were constructed from prefabricated four-by-eight-foot modular panels.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Exterior surfaces were four inches (10 cm) thick, with an aluminum interior surface, and a plywood exterior surface, sandwiching fiberglass.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Skylights were the only windows in flat uniform roof levels, while buildings were connected by a burlap and chicken wire covered tunnel system.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The last of the construction crew departed on January 4, 1957.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The first wintering-over party consisted of eight IGY scientists led by Paul Siple and eight Navy support men led by LTJG John Tuck.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Key components of the camp included an astronomical observatory, a Rawin Tower, a weather balloon inflation shelter, and a 1,000-foot (300 m) snow tunnel with pits for a seismometer and magnetometer.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The lowest average temperatures recorded by the group were in the range −90 °F (−68 °C) to −99 °F (−73 °C), though as Siple points out, "even at −60 °F (−51 °C) I had seen men spitting blood because the capillaries of the bronchial tract frosted".
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On January 3, 1958, Sir Edmund Hillary's team from New Zealand, part of the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition, reached the station over land from Scott Base, followed shortly by Sir Vivian Fuchs' British scientific component.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The buildings of Old Pole were assembled from prefabricated components delivered to the South Pole by air and airdropped.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] They were originally built on the surface, with covered wood-framed walkways connecting the buildings.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Although snow accumulation in open areas at the South Pole is approximately 8 inches (20 cm) per year, wind-blown snow accumulates much more quickly in the vicinity of raised structures.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] By 1960, three years after the construction of the station, it had already been buried by 6 feet (1.8 m) of snow.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station was abandoned in 1975 and became deeply buried, with the pressure causing the mostly wooden roof to cave in.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station was demolished in December 2010, after an equipment operator fell through the structure doing snow stability testing for the National Science Foundation (NSF).
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The area was being vetted for use as a campground for NGO guests.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station was moved in 1975 to the newly constructed Buckminster Fuller geodesic dome 160 feet (50 m) wide by 52 feet (16 m) high, with 46 by 79 feet (14 m × 24 m) steel archways.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] One served as the entry to the dome and it had a transverse arch that contained modular buildings for the station's maintenance, fuel bladders, power plant, snow melter, equipment and vehicles.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Individual buildings within the dome contained the dorms, galley, recreational center, post office and labs for monitoring the upper and lower atmosphere and numerous other complex projects in astronomy and astrophysics.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station also included the Skylab, a box-shaped tower slightly taller than the dome.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Skylab was connected to the Dome by a tunnel.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The Skylab housed atmospheric sensor equipment and later a music room.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the 1970–1974 summers, the Seabees constructing the dome were housed in Korean War era Jamesway huts.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] A hut consists of a wooden frame with a raised platform covered by canvas tarp.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] A double-doored vestibule was at each end.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Although heated, the heat was not sufficient to keep them habitable during the winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] After several burned during the 1976–1977 summer, the construction camp was abandoned and later removed.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] However, in the 1981–1982 season, extra civilian seasonal personnel were housed in a group of Jamesways known as the "summer camp".
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Initially consisting of only two huts, the camp grew to 11 huts housing about 10 people each, plus two recreational huts with bathroom and gym facilities.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In addition, a number of science and berthing structures, such as the hypertats and elevated dormitory, were added in the 1990s, particularly for astronomy and astrophysics.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the period in which the dome served as the main station, many changes to United States South Pole operation took place.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] From the 1990s on, astrophysical research conducted at the South Pole took advantage of its favorable atmospheric conditions and began to produce important scientific results.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Such experiments include the Python, Viper, and DASI telescopes, as well as the 390-inch (10 m) South Pole Telescope.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The DASI telescope has since been decommissioned and its mount used for the Keck Array.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The AMANDA / IceCube experiment makes use of the two-mile (3 km)-thick ice sheet to detect neutrinos which have passed through the earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Pomerantz Observatory (MAPO), was dedicated in 1995.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The importance of these projects changed the priorities in station operation, increasing the status of scientific cargo and personnel.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The 1998–1999 summer season was the last year that VXE-6 with its Lockheed LC-130s serviced the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Beginning in 1999–2000, the New York Air National Guard 109th Airlift Wing took responsibility for the daily cargo and passenger flights between McMurdo Station and the South Pole during the summer.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the winter of 1988 a loud crack was heard in the dome.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Upon investigation it was discovered that the foundation base ring beams were broken due to being overstressed.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] As of 2025, the dome pieces are stored at Port Hueneme, California.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The center oculus is suspended in a display at the Seabee Museum there.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In 1992, the design of a new station began for an 80,000-square-foot (7,400 m2) building with two floor levels that cost US$150 million.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Construction began in 1999, adjacent to the Dome.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The facility was officially dedicated on January 12, 2008, with a ceremony that included the de-commissioning of the old Dome station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The ceremony was attended by a number of dignitaries flown in specifically for the day, including National Science Foundation Director Arden Bement, scientist Susan Solomon and other government officials.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The entirety of building materials to complete the build of the new South Pole Station were flown in from McMurdo Station by the LC-130 Hercules aircraft and the 139th Airlift Squadron Stratton Air National Guard Base, Scotia, New York.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Each plane brought 26,000 pounds (12,000 kg) of cargo each flight with the total weight of the building material being 24,000,000 pounds (11,000,000 kg).
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The new station included a modular design, to accommodate rises in population, and an adjustable elevation to prevent it from being buried in snow.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Since roughly 8 inches (20 cm) of snow accumulates every year without ever thawing, the building's designers included rounded corners and edges around the structure to help reduce snow drifts.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The building faces into the wind with a sloping lower portion of wall.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The angled wall increases the wind speed as it flows under the buildings, and passes above the snow-pack, causing the snow to be scoured away.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This prevents the building from being quickly buried.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Wind tunnel tests show that scouring will continue to occur until the snow level reaches the second floor.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Because snow gradually settles over time under its own weight, the foundations of the building were designed to accommodate substantial differential settling over any one wing in any one line or any one column.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] If differential settling continues, the supported structure will need to be jacked up and re-leveled.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The facility was designed with the primary support columns outboard of the exterior walls so that the entire building can be jacked up a full floor level.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During this process, a new section of column will be added over the existing columns then the jacks pull the building up to the higher elevation.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the summer the station population is typically around 150.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Most personnel leave by the middle of February, leaving a few dozen (39 in 2021) "winter-overs", mostly support staff plus a few scientists, who keep the station functional through the months of Antarctic night.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The winter personnel are isolated between mid-February and late October.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Wintering-over presents notorious dangers and stresses, as the station population is almost totally isolated.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station is completely self-sufficient during the winter, and powered by three generators running on JP-8 jet fuel.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] An annual tradition is a back-to-back-to-back viewing of *The Thing from Another World* (1951), *The Thing* (1982), and *The Thing* (2011) after the last flight has left for the winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Research at the station includes glaciology, geophysics, meteorology, upper atmosphere physics, astronomy, astrophysics, and biomedical studies.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In recent years, most of the winter scientists have worked for the IceCube Neutrino Observatory or for low-frequency astronomy experiments such as the South Pole Telescope and BICEP2.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The low temperature and low moisture content of the polar air, combined with the altitude of over 9,000 feet (2,700 m), causes the air to be far more transparent on some frequencies than is typical elsewhere, and the months of darkness permit sensitive equipment to run constantly.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] There is a small greenhouse at the station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The variety of vegetables and herbs in the greenhouse, which range from fresh eggplant to jalapeños, are all produced hydroponically, using only water and nutrients and no soil.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The greenhouse is the only source of fresh fruit and vegetables during the winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station has a runway for aircraft (ICAO: **NZSP**), 12,000 feet (3,658 m) long.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Between October and February, there are several flights per week of U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Air Force ski-equipped Lockheed LC-130 Hercules aircraft from the New York Air National Guard, 109 AW, 139AS Stratton Air National Guard via McMurdo Station to supply the station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Resupply missions are collectively termed Operation Deep Freeze.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] There is a snow road over the ice sheet from McMurdo, the McMurdo-South Pole highway, which is 994 miles (1,600 km) long.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Data access to the station is provided by NASA's TDRS-4 (non operational), 5 (not radio link to 90°), and 6 (not radio link to 90°) satellites: the DOD DSCS-3 satellite, and the commercial Iridium satellite constellation.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] For the 2007–2008 season, the TDRS relay (named South Pole TDRSS Relay or SPTR) was upgraded to support a data return rate of 50 Mbit/s, which comprises over 90% of the data return capability.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The TDRS-1 satellite formerly provided services to the station, but it failed in October 2009 and was subsequently decommissioned.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Marisat and LES9 were also formerly used.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In July 2016, the GOES-3 satellite was decommissioned due to it nearing the end of its supply of propellant and was replaced by the use of the DSCS-3 satellite, a military communications satellite.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] DSCS-3 can provide a 30 MB/s data rate compared to GOES-3's 1.5 MB/s.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] DSCS-3 and TDRS-4, 5, and 6 are used together to provide the main communications capability for the station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] These satellites provide the data uplink for the station's scientific data as well as provide broadband internet and telecommunications access.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Only during the main satellite events is the station's telephone system able to dial out.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The commercial Iridium satellite is used when the TDRS and DSCS satellites are all out of range to give the station limited communications capability during those times.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During those times, telephone calls may only be made on several Iridium satellite telephone sets owned by the station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station's IT system also has a limited data uplink over the Iridium network, which allows emails less than 100 KB to be sent and received at all times and small critical data files to be transmitted.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This uplink works by bonding the data stream over 12 voice channels.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Non-commercial and non-military communication has been provided by amateur ham radio using primarily HF SSB links today but Morse code and other modes have been used, partly in experiments and mainly in bolstering esprit de corps and hobby-type uses.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The USA sector has the amateur radio call sign prefix run of KC4 and AT; whereas Soviet/Russian stations are known to use 4K1 and others.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The popularity of the hobby during the 1950-80s era saw many ham exchanges between South Polar ham stations and enthusiastic ham operators contacting there from world-wide locations.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Over the years, ham radio has established needed emergency communication to Polar base personnel as well as recreational uses.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Typical of inland Antarctica, Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station experiences an ice cap climate (*EF*) with BWk precipitation patterns.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The peak season of summer lasts from December to mid February.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] At the Amundsen–Scott the average annual precipitation is approximately 25 millimeters (1 inch), primarily falling as snow.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This low level of precipitation is characteristic of the Antarctic interior, where the combination of extremely low temperatures and limited moisture in the atmosphere results in an extremely arid climate with minimal snowfall.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In 1991, Michael Palin visited the base on the eighth and final episode of his BBC Television documentary, *Pole to Pole*.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On January 10, 1995, NASA, PBS, and NSF collaborated for the first live television broadcast from the South Pole, titled *Spaceship South Pole*.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During this interactive broadcast, students from several schools in the United States asked the scientists at the station questions about their work and conditions at the pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In 1999, CBS News correspondent Jerry Bowen reported on camera in a talkback with anchors from the Saturday edition of *CBS This Morning*.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In 1999, the winter-over physician, Jerri Nielsen, found that she had breast cancer.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] She had to rely on self-administered chemotherapy, using supplies from a daring July cargo drop, then was picked up in an equally dangerous mid-October landing.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On May 11, 2000, astrophysicist Rodney Marks became ill while walking between the remote observatory and the base.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] He became increasingly sick over 36 hours, three times returning increasingly distressed to the station's doctor.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Advice was sought by satellite, but Marks died on May 12, 2000, with his condition undiagnosed.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The National Science Foundation issued a statement that Rodney Marks had "apparently died of natural causes, but the specific cause of death had yet to be determined".
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The exact cause of Marks' death could not be determined until his body was removed from Amundsen–Scott Station and flown off Antarctica for an autopsy.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Marks' death was due to methanol poisoning, and the case received media attention as the "first South Pole murder", although there is no evidence that Marks died as the result of the act of another person.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On 26 April 2001, Kenn Borek Air used a DHC-6 Twin Otter aircraft to rescue Dr.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This was the first ever rescue from the South Pole during polar winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] To achieve the range necessary for this flight, the Twin Otter was equipped with a special ferry tank.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In January 2007, the station was visited by a group of high-level Russian officials, including FSB chiefs Nikolai Patrushev and Vladimir Pronichev.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The expedition, led by polar explorer Artur Chilingarov, started from Chile on two Mi-8 helicopters and landed at the South Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On September 6, 2007, The National Geographic Channel's television show *Man Made* aired an episode on the construction of their new facility.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On November 9, 2007, edition of NBC's *Today*, show co-anchor Ann Curry made a satellite telephone call which was broadcast live from the South Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On Christmas 2007, two employees at the base got into a fight and had to be evacuated.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On July 11, 2011, the winter-over communications technician fell ill and was diagnosed with appendicitis.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] An emergency open appendectomy was performed by the station doctors with several winter-overs assisting during the surgery.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The 2011 BBC TV programme *Frozen Planet* discusses the base and shows footage of the inside and outside of the elevated station in the "Last Frontier Episode".
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] During the 2011 winter-over season, station manager Renee-Nicole Douceur experienced a stroke on August 27, resulting in loss of vision and cognitive function.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Because the Amundsen–Scott base lacks diagnostic medical equipment such as an MRI or CT scan machine, station doctors were unable to fully evaluate the damage done by the stroke or the chance of recurrence.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Physicians on site recommended a medevac flight as soon as possible for Douceur, but offsite doctors hired by Raytheon Polar Services (the company contracted to run the base) and the National Science Foundation disagreed with the severity of the situation.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The National Science Foundation, which is the final authority on all flights and assumes all financial responsibility for the flights, denied the request for medevac, saying the weather was still too hazardous.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Plans were made to evacuate Douceur on the first flight available.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Douceur was evacuated, along with a doctor and an escort, on an October 17 cargo flight.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This was the first flight available when the weather window opened up on October 16.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] This first flight is usually solely for supply and refueling of the station, and does not customarily accept passengers, as the plane's cabin is unpressurized.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The evacuation was successful, and Douceur arrived in Christchurch, New Zealand, at 10:55 p.m.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In March 2014, BICEP2 announced that they had detected B-modes from gravitational waves generated in the early universe, supporting the inflation theory of cosmology.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Later analysis showed that BICEP only saw polarized dust signal in the galaxy and not primordial B-modes.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] On 20 June 2016, there was another medical evacuation of two personnel around midwinter day, again involving Kenn Borek Air and DHC-6 Twin Otter aircraft.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In December 2016, Buzz Aldrin was visiting the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station, Antarctica, as part of a tourist group, when he fell ill and was evacuated, first to McMurdo Station and from there to Christchurch, New Zealand, where he was reported to be in stable condition.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Aldrin's visit at age 86 makes him the oldest person to ever reach the South Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] In the summer of 2016–17, Anthony Bourdain filmed part of an episode of his television show *Anthony Bourdain: Parts Unknown* at the station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Science and life at the Amundsen-Scott South Pole station is documented in Dr.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] John Bird's award-winning book, *One Day, One Night: Portraits of the South Pole* which chronicles the South Pole Foucault Pendulum, the 300 Club, the first midwinter medevac, and science at the Pole including climate change and cosmology.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Science fiction author Kim Stanley Robinson's book *Antarctica* features a fictionalized account of the culture at Amundsen–Scott and McMurdo, set in the near future.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station is featured prominently in the 1998 *The X-Files* film *Fight the Future*.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The 2019 film *Where'd You Go, Bernadette* features the station prominently and includes scenes of its construction at the closing credits, although the actual station depicted in the film is Halley VI British Antarctic Research Station.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The South Pole sees the Sun rise and set only once a year.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] Due to atmospheric refraction, these do not occur exactly on the September equinox and the March equinox, respectively: the Sun is above the horizon for four days longer at each equinox.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The place has no solar time; there is no daily maximum or minimum solar height above the horizon.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The station uses New Zealand time (UTC+12 during standard time and UTC+13 during daylight saving time) since all flights to McMurdo station depart from Christchurch and, therefore, all official travel from the pole goes through New Zealand.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] The zone identifier in the IANA time zone database was the deprecated Antarctica/South_Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/amundsen-scott-south-pole-station] It now uses the Pacific/Auckland timezone.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica-novel] Most of the story centers on McMurdo Station, the largest settlement in Antarctica, which is run as a scientific research station by the United States.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica-novel] In addition to McMurdo, the story involves the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station, the Shackleton Glacier, the McMurdo Dry Valleys and a South American drilling platform near Roberts Massif.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica-novel] The novel was heavily influenced by Robinson's 1995 stay in Antarctica through the National Science Foundation's Antarctic Artists and Writers Program.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica-novel] The novel was nominated for a Locus Award in 1998.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica-novel] Although the novel was thoroughly researched and generally realistic, some reviews noted that the book was slowed down in places by heavy technical and historic detail.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is, on average, the coldest, driest, and windiest of the continents, and has the highest average elevation.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It is mainly a polar desert, with annual precipitation of over 200 mm (8 in) along the coast and far less inland.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] About 70% of the world's freshwater reserves are frozen in Antarctica, which, if melted, would raise global sea levels by almost 60 metres (200 ft).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica holds the record for the lowest measured temperature on Earth, −89.2 °C (−128.6 °F).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The coastal regions can reach temperatures over 10 °C (50 °F) in the summer.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Native species of animals include mites, nematodes, penguins, seals and tardigrades.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Where vegetation occurs, it is mostly in the form of lichen or moss.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The ice shelves of Antarctica were probably first seen in 1820, during a Russian expedition led by Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen and Mikhail Lazarev.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The decades that followed saw further exploration by French, American, and British expeditions.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first confirmed landing was by a Norwegian team in 1895.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In the early 20th century, there were a few expeditions into the interior of the continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] British explorers Douglas Mawson, Edgeworth David, and Alistair Mackay were the first to reach the magnetic South Pole in 1909, and the geographic South Pole was first reached in 1911 by Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is governed by about 30 countries, all of which are parties of the 1959 Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] According to the terms of the treaty, military activity, mining, nuclear explosions, and nuclear waste disposal are all prohibited in Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Tourism, fishing and research are the main human activities in and around Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the summer months, about 5,000 people reside at research stations, a figure that drops to around 1,000 in the winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Despite the continent's remoteness, human activity has a significant effect on it via pollution, ozone depletion, and climate change.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The name given to the continent originates from the word *antarctic*, which comes from Middle French *antartique* or *antarctique* ('opposite to the Arctic') and, in turn, the Latin *antarcticus* ('opposite to the north').
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] *Antarcticus* is derived from the Greek ἀντι- ('anti-') and ἀρκτικός (*arktikos*, 'of the Bear [Ursa Major], northern').
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Greek philosopher Aristotle wrote in *Meteorology* about an "Antarctic region" in c.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Greek geographer Marinus of Tyre reportedly used the name in his world map from the second century AD, now lost.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] European ideas regarding the existence of a *Terra Australis*—a vast continent in the far south of the globe to balance the northern lands of Europe, Asia, and North Africa—had existed as an intellectual concept since classical antiquity.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] *Terra Australis* was therefore the name used to refer to all hypothetical landmasses proposed to be where Antarctica is now known to exist.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Assertion of the presence of such a land lasted until the European discovery of Australia.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the early 19th century, explorer Matthew Flinders doubted the existence of a detached continent south of Australia (then called New Holland) and thus advocated for the "Terra Australis" name to be used for Australia instead.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 1824, the colonial authorities in Sydney officially renamed the continent of New Holland to Australia, leaving the term "Terra Australis" unavailable as a reference to Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Over the following decades, geographers used phrases such as "the Antarctic Continent".
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] They searched for a more poetic replacement, suggesting names such as *Ultima* and *Antipodea*.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] *Antarctica* was adopted in the 1890s, with the first use of the name being attributed to the Scottish cartographer John George Bartholomew.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Positioned asymmetrically around the South Pole and largely south of the Antarctic Circle (one of the five major circles of latitude that mark maps of the world), Antarctica is surrounded by the Southern Ocean.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Rivers exist in Antarctica; the longest is the Onyx.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica covers more than 14.2 million km2 (5,500,000 sq mi), almost double the area of Australia, making it the fifth-largest continent, and comparable to the surface area of Pluto.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Its coastline is almost 18,000 km (11,200 mi) long: as of 1983, of the four coastal types, 44% of the coast is floating ice in the form of an ice shelf, 38% consists of ice walls that rest on rock, 13% is ice streams or the edge of glaciers, and the remaining 5% is exposed rock.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The lakes that lie at the base of the continental ice sheet occur mainly in the McMurdo Dry Valleys or various oases.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Lake Vostok, discovered beneath Russia's Vostok Station, is the largest subglacial lake globally and one of the largest lakes in the world.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It was once believed that the lake had been sealed off for millions of years, but scientists now estimate its water is replaced by the slow melting and freezing of ice caps every 13,000 years.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the summer, the ice at the edges of the lakes can melt, and liquid moats temporarily form.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica has both saline and freshwater lakes.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is divided into West Antarctica and East Antarctica by the Transantarctic Mountains, which stretch from Victoria Land to the Ross Sea.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The vast majority of Antarctica is covered by the Antarctic ice sheet, which averages 1.9 km (1.2 mi) in thickness.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The ice sheet extends to all but a few oases, which, with the exception of the McMurdo Dry Valleys, are located in coastal areas.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Several Antarctic ice streams flow to one of the many Antarctic ice shelves, a process described by ice-sheet dynamics.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] East Antarctica comprises Coats Land, Queen Maud Land, Enderby Land, Mac.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Robertson Land, Wilkes Land, and Victoria Land.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] All but a small portion of the region lies within the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] East Antarctica is largely covered by the East Antarctic Ice Sheet.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are numerous islands surrounding Antarctica, most of which are volcanic and very young by geological standards.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The most prominent exceptions to this are the islands of the Kerguelen Plateau, the earliest of which formed around 40 Ma.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Vinson Massif, in the Ellsworth Mountains, is the highest peak in Antarctica at 4,892 m (16,050 ft).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Mount Erebus on Ross Island is the world's southernmost active volcano and erupts around 10 times each day.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Ash from eruptions has been found 300 kilometres (190 mi) from the volcanic crater.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There is evidence of a large number of volcanoes under the ice, which could pose a risk to the ice sheet if activity levels were to rise.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The ice dome known as Dome Argus in East Antarctica is the highest Antarctic ice feature, at 4,091 metres (13,422 ft).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It is one of the world's coldest and driest places—temperatures there reach as low as −90 °C (−130 °F), and the annual precipitation is 1–3 cm (0.39–1.18 in).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] From the end of the Neoproterozoic era to the Cretaceous, Antarctica was part of the supercontinent Gondwana.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Modern Antarctica was formed as Gondwana gradually broke apart beginning around 183 Ma.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] For a large proportion of the Phanerozoic, Antarctica had a tropical or temperate climate, and it was covered in forests.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the Cambrian period, Gondwana had a mild climate.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] West Antarctica was partially in the Northern Hemisphere, and during the time, large amounts of sandstones, limestones, and shales were deposited.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] East Antarctica was at the equator, where seafloor invertebrates and trilobites flourished in the tropical seas.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] By the start of the Devonian period (416 Ma), Gondwana was in more southern latitudes, and the climate was cooler, though fossils of land plants are known from then.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Sand and silts were laid down in what is now the Ellsworth, Horlick, and Pensacola Mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica became glaciated during the Late Paleozoic icehouse beginning at the end of the Devonian period (360 Ma), though glaciation would substantially increase during the late Carboniferous.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It drifted closer to the South Pole, and the climate cooled, though flora remained.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] After deglaciation during the latter half of the Early Permian, the land became dominated by glossopterids (an extinct group of seed plants with no close living relatives), most prominently *Glossopteris*, a tree interpreted as growing in waterlogged soils, which formed extensive coal deposits.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Other plants found in Antarctica during the Permian include Cordaitales, sphenopsids, ferns, and lycophytes.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] At the end of the Permian, the climate became drier and hotter over much of Gondwana, and the glossopterid forest ecosystems collapsed as part of the Permian–Triassic extinction event.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There is no evidence of any tetrapods having lived in Antarctica during the Paleozoic.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The continued warming dried out much of Gondwana.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the Triassic period, Antarctica was dominated by seed ferns (pteridosperms) belonging to the genus *Dicroidium*, which grew as trees.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Other associated Triassic flora included ginkgophytes, cycadophytes, conifers, and sphenopsids.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Tetrapods first appeared in Antarctica during the Early Triassic epoch, with the earliest known fossils found in the Fremouw Formation of the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Synapsids (also known as "mammal-like reptiles") included species such as *Lystrosaurus*, and were common during the Early Triassic.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Antarctic Peninsula began to form during the Jurassic period (206 to 146 million years ago).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Africa separated from Antarctica in the Jurassic around 160 Ma, followed by the Indian subcontinent in the early Cretaceous (about 125 Ma).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] *Ginkgo* trees, conifers, Bennettitales, horsetails, ferns and cycads were plentiful during the time.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] About 80 million years ago, flowering plants became the most diverse groups of plants on the continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In West Antarctica, coniferous forests dominated throughout the Cretaceous period (146–66 Ma), though southern beech trees (*Nothofagus*) became prominent towards the end of the Cretaceous.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the early Paleogene, the Antarctic land bridge continued to connect Antarctica with South America as well as to southeastern Australia.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Fauna from the La Meseta Formation in the Antarctic Peninsula, dating to the Eocene, is very similar to equivalent South American faunas; with marsupials, xenarthrans, litoptern, and astrapotherian ungulates, as well as gondwanatheres and possibly meridiolestidans.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Marsupials are thought to have dispersed into Australia from South America via Antarctica by the early Eocene.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Around 53 Ma, Australia-New Guinea separated from Antarctica, opening the Tasmanian Passage.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Drake Passage opened between Antarctica and South America around 30 Ma, resulting in the creation of the Antarctic Circumpolar Current that completely isolated the continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Models of Antarctic geography suggest that this current, as well as a feedback loop caused by lowering CO2 levels, caused the creation of small yet permanent polar ice caps.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] As CO2 levels declined further the ice began to spread rapidly, replacing the forests that until then had covered Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Tundra ecosystems continued to exist on Antarctica until around 14–10 million years ago, when further cooling lead to their extermination.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The geology of Antarctica, largely obscured by the continental ice sheet, can be studied via techniques such as remote sensing, ground-penetrating radar, and satellite imagery.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Geologically, West Antarctica closely resembles the South American Andes.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Antarctic Peninsula was formed by geologic uplift and the transformation of sea bed sediments into metamorphic rocks.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] West Antarctica was formed by the merging of several continental plates, which created a number of mountain ranges in the region, the most prominent being the Ellsworth Mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The presence of the West Antarctic Rift System has resulted in volcanism along the border between West and East Antarctica, as well as the creation of the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Its formation began during the Archean Eon (4,000 Ma–2,500 Ma), and stopped during the Cambrian Period.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It is built on a craton of rock, which is the basis of the Precambrian Shield.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] On top of the base are coal and sandstones, limestones, and shales that were laid down during the Devonian and Jurassic periods to form the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In coastal areas such as the Shackleton Range and Victoria Land, some faulting has occurred.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Coal was first recorded in Antarctica near the Beardmore Glacier by Frank Wild on the *Nimrod* Expedition in 1907, and low-grade coal is known to exist across many parts of the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Prince Charles Mountains contain deposits of iron ore.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are oil and natural gas fields in the Ross Sea.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is the coldest, windiest, and driest of Earth's continents.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Near the coast, the temperature can exceed 10 °C in summer and fall to below −40 °C in winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Over the elevated inland, it can rise to about −30 °C in summer but fall below −80 °C in winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The lowest natural air temperature ever recorded on Earth was −89.2 °C (−128.6 °F) at the Russian Vostok Station in Antarctica on 21 July 1983.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] A lower air temperature of −94.7 °C (−138.5 °F) was recorded in 2010 by satellite—however, it may have been influenced by ground temperatures and was not recorded at a height of 2 m (7 ft) above the surface as required for official air temperature records.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is colder than the Arctic region, as much of Antarctica is over 3,000 m (9,800 ft) above sea level, where air temperatures are colder.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The relative warmth of the Arctic Ocean is transferred through the Arctic sea ice and moderates temperatures in the Arctic region.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is a polar desert with little precipitation; the continent receives an average equivalent to about 150 mm (6 in) of water per year, mostly in the form of snow.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The interior is drier and receives less than 50 mm (2 in) per year, whereas the coastal regions typically receive more than 200 mm (8 in).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In a few blue-ice areas, the wind and sublimation remove more snow than is accumulated by precipitation.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In the dry valleys, the same effect occurs over a rock base, leading to a barren and desiccated landscape.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] East Antarctica is colder than its western counterpart because of its higher elevation.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Weather fronts rarely penetrate far into the continent, leaving the centre cold and dry, with moderate wind speeds.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Heavy snowfalls are common on the coastal portion of Antarctica, where snowfalls of up to 1.22 m (48 in) in 48 hours have been recorded.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] At the continent's edge, strong katabatic winds off the polar plateau often blow at storm force.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the summer, more solar radiation reaches the surface at the South Pole than at the equator because of the 24 hours of sunlight received there each day.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica's average ice mass change since 2002 has been on the order of 100 billion metric tons per year.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The extent (area) of Antarctic sea ice reached a new low in 2023.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Chart shows how little sea ice remains in the Antarctic summer, which at one point in February 2023 was only about 60% of its 1981–2010 average.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Despite its isolation, Antarctica has experienced warming and ice loss in recent decades, driven by greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] West Antarctica warmed by over 0.1 °C per decade from the 1950s to the 2000s, and the exposed Antarctic Peninsula has warmed by 3 °C (5.4 °F) since the mid-20th century.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The colder, stabler East Antarctica did not show any warming until the 2000s.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Around Antarctica, the Southern Ocean has absorbed more oceanic heat than any other ocean, and has seen strong warming at depths below 2,000 m (6,600 ft).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Around the West Antarctic, the ocean has warmed by 1 °C (1.8 °F) since 1955.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The warming of the Southern Ocean around Antarctica has caused the weakening or collapse of ice shelves, which float just offshore of glaciers and stabilize them.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Many coastal glaciers have been losing mass and retreating, causing net ice loss across Antarctica although the East Antarctic ice sheet continues to gain ice inland.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] By 2100, net ice loss from Antarctica is expected to add about 11 cm (5 in) to global sea level rise.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Marine ice sheet instability may cause West Antarctica to contribute tens of centimeters more if it is triggered before 2100.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] With higher warming, instability would be much more likely and could double the 21st-century global sea level rise.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The fresh meltwater from the ice dilutes the saline Antarctic bottom water weakening the lower cell of the Southern Ocean overturning circulation (SOOC).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] According to some research, a full collapse of the SOOC may occur at between 1.7 °C (3.1 °F) and 3 °C (5.4 °F) of global warming although the full effects are expected to occur over multiple centuries.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] They include less precipitation in the Southern Hemisphere but more in the Northern Hemisphere, an eventual decline of fisheries in the Southern Ocean and a potential collapse of certain marine ecosystems.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] While many Antarctic species remain undiscovered, there are documented increases in Antarctic flora, and large fauna such as penguins are already having difficulty retaining suitable habitat.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] On ice-free land, permafrost thaws release greenhouse gases and formerly frozen pollution.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctic warming and associated changes in Southern Ocean circulation can also influence climate patterns in parts of Africa, affecting regional rainfall and temperature variability.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The West Antarctic ice sheet is likely to melt completely unless temperatures are reduced by 2 °C (3.6 °F) below 2020 levels.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The loss of that ice sheet would take between 500 and 13,000 years.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] A sea level rise of 3.3 m (10 ft 10 in) would occur if the ice sheet collapses, which would leave ice caps on the mountains, and a rise of 4.3 m (14 ft 1 in) would occur if those ice caps also melt.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The far more stable East Antarctic ice sheet may cause a sea level rise of only 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) to 0.9 m (2 ft 11 in) from the current level of warming, a small fraction of the 53.3 m (175 ft) contained in the full ice sheet.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] With global warming being around 3 °C (5.4 °F), vulnerable areas like Wilkes Basin and Aurora Basin may collapse over around 2,000 years, potentially adding up to 6.4 m (21 ft 0 in) to sea levels.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Scientists have studied the ozone layer in the atmosphere above Antarctica since the 1970s.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 1985, British scientists, working on data they had gathered at Halley Research Station on the Brunt Ice Shelf, discovered a large area of low ozone concentration over Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The 'ozone hole' covers almost the whole continent and was at its largest in September 2006; the longest-lasting event occurred in 2020.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The depletion is caused by the emission of chlorofluorocarbons and halons into the atmosphere, which causes ozone to break down into other gases.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The extreme cold conditions of Antarctica allow polar stratospheric clouds to form.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The clouds act as catalysts for chemical reactions, which eventually lead to the destruction of ozone.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The 1987 Montreal Protocol has restricted the emissions of ozone-depleting substances.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The ozone hole above Antarctica is predicted to slowly disappear; by the 2060s, levels of ozone are expected to have returned to values last recorded in the 1980s.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The ozone depletion can cause a cooling of around 6 °C (11 °F) in the stratosphere.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The cooling strengthens the polar vortex and so prevents the outflow of the cold air near the South Pole, which in turn cools the continental mass of the East Antarctic ice sheet.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The peripheral areas of Antarctica, especially the Antarctic Peninsula, are then subjected to higher temperatures, which accelerate the melting of the ice.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Models suggest that ozone depletion and the enhanced polar vortex effect may also account for the period of increasing sea ice extent, lasting from when observation started in the late 1970s until 2014.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Since then, the coverage of Antarctic sea ice has decreased rapidly.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Most species in Antarctica seem to be the descendants of species that lived there millions of years ago.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] As such, they must have survived multiple glacial cycles.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The species survived the periods of extremely cold climate in isolated warmer areas, such as those with geothermal heat or areas that remained ice-free throughout the colder climate.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Invertebrate life of Antarctica includes species of microscopic mites such as *Alaskozetes antarcticus*, lice, fleas (*Glaciopsyllus antarcticus*), nematodes, tardigrades, rotifers, krill and springtails.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The flightless midge *Belgica antarctica*, the largest purely terrestrial animal in Antarctica, reaches 6 mm (1⁄4 in) in size.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctic krill, which congregates in large schools, is the keystone species of the ecosystem of the Southern Ocean, being an important food organism for whales, seals, leopard seals, fur seals, squid, icefish, and many bird species, such as penguins and albatrosses.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Some species of marine animals exist and rely, directly or indirectly, on phytoplankton.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctic sea life includes penguins, blue whales, orcas, colossal squids and fur seals.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Antarctic fur seal was very heavily hunted in the 18th and 19th centuries for its pelt by seal hunters from the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Leopard seals are apex predators in the Antarctic ecosystem and migrate across the Southern Ocean in search of food.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are approximately 40 bird species that breed on or close to Antarctica, including species of petrels, penguins, cormorants, and gulls.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Various other bird species visit the ocean around Antarctica, including some that normally reside in the Arctic.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The emperor penguin is the only penguin that breeds during the winter in Antarctica; it and the Adélie penguin breed farther south than any other penguin.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] A Census of Marine Life by some 500 researchers during the International Polar Year was released in 2010.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The research found that more than 235 marine organisms live in both polar regions, having bridged the gap of 12,000 km (7,456 mi).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Large animals such as some cetaceans and birds make the round trip annually.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Smaller forms of life, such as sea cucumbers and free-swimming snails, are also found in both polar oceans.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Factors that may aid in their distribution include temperature differences between the deep ocean at the poles and the equator of no more than 5 °C (9 °F) and the major current systems or marine conveyor belts which are able to transport eggs and larva.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In January 2025, the detachment of the massive iceberg A-84 (comparable in size to the city of Chicago) from the George VI Ice Shelf provided a rare opportunity to explore the seafloor beneath floating ice shelves using robotic submersibles.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Researchers uncovered ecosystems unexpectedly rich in large corals, ancient sponges, icefish, giant sea spiders, and even octopuses at depths of up to 1,300 metres (4,300 ft).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] These ecosystems may harbor novel species that have remained concealed for centuries, sustained by nutrient-bearing ocean currents.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] About 1,150 species of fungi have been recorded in the Antarctic region, of which about 750 are non-lichen-forming.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Some of the species, having evolved under extreme conditions, have colonised structural cavities within porous rocks and have contributed to shaping the rock formations of the McMurdo Dry Valleys and surrounding mountain ridges.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The simplified morphology of such fungi, along with their similar biological structures, metabolism systems capable of remaining active at very low temperatures, and reduced life cycles, make them well suited to such environments.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Their thick-walled and strongly melanised cells make them resistant to UV radiation.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] An Antarctic endemic species, the crust-like lichen *Buellia frigida*, has been used as a model organism in astrobiology research.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The same features can be observed in algae and cyanobacteria, suggesting that they are adaptations to the conditions prevailing in Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] This has led to speculation that life on Mars might have been similar to Antarctic fungi, such as *Cryomyces antarcticus* and *Cryomyces minteri*.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Some of the species of fungi, which are apparently endemic to Antarctica, live in bird dung, and have evolved so they can grow inside extremely cold dung, but can also pass through the intestines of warm-blooded animals.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Throughout its history, Antarctica has seen a wide variety of plant life.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In the Cretaceous, it was dominated by a fern-conifer ecosystem, which changed into a temperate rainforest by the end of that period.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the colder Neogene (17–2.5 Ma), a tundra ecosystem replaced the rainforests.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The climate of present-day Antarctica does not allow extensive vegetation to form.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] A combination of freezing temperatures, poor soil quality, and a lack of moisture and sunlight inhibit plant growth, causing low species diversity and limited distribution.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The flora largely consists of bryophytes (25 species of liverworts and 100 species of mosses).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are three species of flowering plants, all of which are found in the Antarctic Peninsula: *Deschampsia antarctica* (Antarctic hair grass), *Colobanthus quitensis* (Antarctic pearlwort) and the non-native *Poa annua* (annual bluegrass).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Of the 700 species of algae in Antarctica, around half are marine phytoplankton.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Multicoloured snow algae are especially abundant in the coastal regions during the summer.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Even sea ice can harbour unique ecological communities, as it expels all salt from the water when it freezes, which accumulates into pockets of brine that also harbour dormant microorganisms.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] When the ice begins to melt, brine pockets expand and can combine to form brine channels, and the algae inside the pockets can reawaken and thrive until the next freeze.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Bacteria have also been found as deep as 800 m (0.50 mi) under the ice.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It is thought to be likely that there exists a native bacterial community within the subterranean water body of Lake Vostok.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The existence of life there is thought to strengthen the argument for the possibility of life on Jupiter's moon Europa, which may have water beneath its water-ice crust.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There exists a community of extremophile bacteria in the highly alkaline waters of Lake Untersee.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The prevalence of highly resilient creatures in such inhospitable areas could further bolster the argument for extraterrestrial life in cold, methane-rich environments.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first international agreement to protect Antarctica's biodiversity was adopted in 1964.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The overfishing of krill (an animal that plays a large role in the Antarctic ecosystem) led officials to enact regulations on fishing.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Convention for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources, an international treaty that came into force in 1980, regulates fisheries, aiming to preserve ecological relationships.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Despite these regulations, illegal fishing—particularly of the highly prized Patagonian toothfish which is marketed as Chilean sea bass in the U.S.—remains a problem.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In analogy to the 1980 treaty on sustainable fishing, countries led by New Zealand and the United States negotiated a treaty on mining.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] This Convention on the Regulation of Antarctic Mineral Resource Activities was adopted in 1988.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] After a strong campaign from environmental organisations, first Australia and then France decided not to ratify the treaty.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Instead, countries adopted the Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty (the Madrid Protocol), which entered into force in 1998.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Madrid Protocol bans all mining, designating the continent as a "natural reserve devoted to peace and science".
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The pressure group Greenpeace established a base on Ross Island from 1987 to 1992 as part of its attempt to establish the continent as a World Park.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Southern Ocean Whale Sanctuary was established in 1994 by the International Whaling Commission.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It covers 50 million km2 (19 million sq mi) and completely surrounds the Antarctic continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] All commercial whaling is banned in the zone, though Japan has continued to hunt whales in the area, ostensibly for research purposes.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Despite these protections, the biodiversity in Antarctica is still at risk from human activities.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Specially protected areas cover less than 2% of the area and provide better protection for animals with popular appeal than for less visible animals.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are more terrestrial protected areas than marine protected areas.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Ecosystems are impacted by local and global threats, notably pollution, the invasion of non-native species, and the various effects of climate change.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Early world maps, like the 1513 Piri Reis map, feature the hypothetical continent *Terra Australis*.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Much larger than and unrelated to Antarctica, *Terra Australis* was a landmass that classical scholars presumed necessary to balance the known lands in the northern hemisphere.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Captain James Cook's ships, HMS *Resolution* and *Adventure*, crossed the Antarctic Circle on 17 January 1773, in December 1773, and again in January 1774.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Cook came within about 120 km (75 mi) of the Antarctic coast before retreating in the face of field ice in January 1773.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 1775, he called the existence of a polar continent "probable", and in another copy of his journal he wrote: "[I] firmly believe it and it's more than probable that we have seen a part of it".
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Sealers were among the earliest to go closer to the Antarctic landmass, perhaps in the earlier part of the 19th century.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The oldest known human remains in the Antarctic region was a skull, dated from 1819 to 1825, that belonged to a young woman on Yamana Beach at the South Shetland Islands.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The woman, who was likely to have been part of a sealing expedition, was found in 1985.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first person to see Antarctica or its ice shelf was long thought to have been the British sailor Edward Bransfield, a captain in the Royal Navy, who discovered the tip of the Antarctic peninsula on 30 January 1820.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] However, a captain in the Imperial Russian Navy, Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen, recorded seeing an ice shelf on 27 January.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The American sealer Nathaniel Palmer, whose sealing ship was in the region at this time, may also have been the first to sight the Antarctic Peninsula.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The sighting happened three days before Bransfield sighted the land of the Trinity Peninsula of Antarctica, as opposed to the ice of an ice shelf, and 10 months before Palmer did so in November 1820.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first documented landing on Antarctica was by the English-born American sealer John Davis, apparently at Hughes Bay on 7 February 1821, although some historians dispute this claim, as there is no evidence Davis landed on the Antarctic continent rather than an offshore island.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The American captain Charles Wilkes led an expedition in 1838–1839 and was the first to claim he had discovered the continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The British naval officer James Clark Ross failed to realise that what he referred to as "the various patches of land recently discovered by the American, French and English navigators on the verge of the Antarctic Circle" were connected to form a single continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The American explorer Mercator Cooper landed on East Antarctica on 26 January 1853.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first confirmed landing on the continental mass of Antarctica occurred in 1895 when the Norwegian-Swedish whaling ship *Antarctic* reached Cape Adare.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the *Nimrod* Expedition led by the British explorer Ernest Shackleton in 1907, parties led by Edgeworth David became the first to climb Mount Erebus and to reach the south magnetic pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Douglas Mawson, who assumed the leadership of the Magnetic Pole party on their perilous return, retired in 1931.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Between December 1908 and February 1909, Shackleton and three members of his expedition became the first humans to traverse the Ross Ice Shelf, the first to cross the Transantarctic Mountains (via the Beardmore Glacier), and the first to set foot on the south Polar Plateau.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] On 14 December 1911, an expedition led by Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen from the ship *Fram* became the first to reach the geographic South Pole, using a route from the Bay of Whales and up the Axel Heiberg Glacier.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] One month later, the doomed *Terra Nova* Expedition reached the pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Byrd led four expeditions to Antarctica during the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s, using the first mechanised tractors.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] His expeditions conducted extensive geographical and scientific research, and he is credited with surveying a larger region of the continent than any other explorer.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 1937, Ingrid Christensen became the first woman to step onto the Antarctic mainland.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Caroline Mikkelsen had landed on an island of Antarctica, earlier in 1935.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The South Pole was next reached on 31 October 1956, when a U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Navy group led by Rear Admiral George J.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Six women were flown to the South Pole as a publicity stunt in 1969.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In the summer of 1996–1997, Norwegian explorer Børge Ousland became the first person to cross Antarctica alone from coast to coast, helped by a kite on parts of the journey.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Ousland holds the record for the fastest unsupported journey to the South Pole, taking 34 days.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first semi-permanent inhabitants of regions near Antarctica (areas situated south of the Antarctic Convergence) were British and American sealers who used to spend a year or more on South Georgia, from 1786 onward.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] During the whaling era, which lasted until 1966, the population of the island varied from over 1,000 in the summer (over 2,000 in some years) to some 200 in the winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Most of the whalers were Norwegian, with an increasing proportion from Britain.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first child born in the southern polar region was a Norwegian girl, Solveig Gunbjørg Jacobsen, born in Grytviken on 8 October 1913.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Emilio Marcos Palma was the first person born on the Antarctic mainland at the Esperanza Base of the Argentine Army, on 7 January 1978.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica's population consists mostly of the staff of research stations in Antarctica (which are continuously maintained despite the population decline in the winter), although there are 2 all-civilian bases in Antarctica: the Esperanza Base and the Villa Las Estrellas base.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The number of people conducting and supporting scientific research and other work on the continent and its nearby islands varies from about 1,200 in winter to about 4,800 in the summer, with an additional 136 people in the winter to 266 people in the summer from the 2 civilian bases (as of 2017).
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Some of the research stations are staffed year-round, the winter-over personnel typically arriving from their home countries for a one-year assignment.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Christianity is the most common Antarctic religion, with 8 chapels of various Christian denominations located there; due to the difficulties involved with transporting religious officials to the continent most services are performed online.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctic English, a distinct variety of the English language, has been found to be spoken by people living on Antarctica and the subantarctic islands.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica's status is regulated by the 1959 Antarctic Treaty and other related agreements, collectively called the Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica is defined as all land and ice shelves south of 60° S for the purposes of the Treaty System.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The treaty was signed by twelve countries, including the Soviet Union, the United Kingdom, Argentina, Chile, Australia, and the United States.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Since 1959, a further 42 countries have acceded to the treaty.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Countries can participate in decision-making if they can demonstrate that they do significant research on Antarctica; as of 2022, 29 countries have this 'consultative status'.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Decisions are based on consensus, instead of a vote.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The treaty set aside Antarctica as a scientific preserve and established freedom of scientific investigation and environmental protection.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Several countries with research stations in Antarctica allow their citizens stationed in the continent to vote in their elections.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 1539, the King of Spain, Charles V, created the Governorate of Terra Australis, which encompassed lands south of the Strait of Magellan and thus the then-hypothetical Antarctica, granting this Governorate to Pedro Sancho de la Hoz.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Spain claimed all the territories to the south of the Strait of Magellan until the South Pole, with eastern and western borders to these claims specified in the Treaty of Tordesillas and Zaragoza respectively.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 1555 the claim was incorporated to Chile.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In the present, sovereignty over regions of Antarctica is claimed by seven different countries.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] While a few of these countries have mutually recognised each other's claims, the validity of the claims is not recognised universally.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] New claims on Antarctica have been suspended since 1959, although in 2015, Norway formally defined Queen Maud Land as including the unclaimed area between it and the South Pole.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Argentine, British, and Chilean claims overlap and have caused friction.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 2012, after the British Foreign & Commonwealth Office designated a previously unnamed area Queen Elizabeth Land in tribute to Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee, the Argentine government protested against the claim.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The UK passed some of the areas it claimed to Australia and New Zealand after they achieved independence.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The claims by Britain, Australia, New Zealand, France, and Norway do not overlap and are recognised by each other.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Other member nations of the Antarctic Treaty do not recognise any claim, yet have shown some form of territorial interest in the past.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Deposits of coal, hydrocarbons, iron ore, platinum, copper, chromium, nickel, gold, and other minerals have been found in Antarctica, but not in large enough quantities to extract.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty, which came into effect in 1998 and is due to be reviewed in 2048, restricts the exploitation of Antarctic resources, including minerals.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Tourists have been visiting Antarctica since 1957.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Tourism is subject to the provisions of the Antarctic Treaty and Environmental Protocol; the self-regulatory body for the industry is the International Association of Antarctica Tour Operators.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Tourists arrive by small or medium ship at specific scenic locations with accessible concentrations of iconic wildlife.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Much Antarctic tourism is based around bird watching tours due to the high numbers of penguins on the continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] McDonald Beach is known to be a high-traffic area for tourists watching the Adélie penguin population there.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Overland sightseeing flights operated out of Australia and New Zealand until the Mount Erebus disaster in 1979, when an Air New Zealand plane crashed into Mount Erebus, killing all of the 257 people on board.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Qantas resumed commercial overflights to Antarctica from Australia in the mid-1990s.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Over 74,000 tourists visited the region during the 2019–2020 season, of which 18,500 travelled on cruise ships but did not leave them to explore on land.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Some nature conservation groups have expressed concern over the potential adverse effects caused by the influx of visitors and have called for limits on the size of visiting cruise ships and a tourism quota.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The primary response by Antarctic Treaty parties has been to develop guidelines that set landing limits and closed or restricted zones on the more frequently visited sites.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] In 2017, there were more than 4,400 scientists undertaking research in Antarctica, a number that fell to just over 1,100 in the winter.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are over 70 permanent and seasonal research stations on the continent; the largest, United States' McMurdo Station, is capable of housing more than 1,000 people.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The British Antarctic Survey has five major research stations on Antarctica, one of which is completely portable.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Belgian Princess Elisabeth station is one of the most modern stations and the first to be carbon-neutral.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Argentina, Australia, Chile, and Russia also have a large scientific presence on Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Many nations release strategy reports designed to guide their research efforts on Antarctica.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The British Antarctic Survey (BAS), Australian Antarctic Program (AAP) and United States Antarctic Program (USAP) have all released such reports, largely focusing on how changes in Antarctica's climate may impact their respective home countries and the global climate.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Geologists primarily study plate tectonics, meteorites, and the breakup of Gondwana.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Glaciologists study the history and dynamics of floating ice, seasonal snow, glaciers, and ice sheets.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Biologists, in addition to researching wildlife, are interested in how low temperatures and the presence of humans affect adaptation and survival strategies in organisms.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Biomedical scientists have made discoveries concerning the spreading of viruses and the body's response to extreme seasonal temperatures.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The view of space from Earth is improved by a thinner atmosphere at higher elevations and a lack of water vapour in the atmosphere caused by freezing temperatures.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Astrophysicists at the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station study cosmic microwave background radiation and neutrinos from space.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The largest neutrino detector in the world, the IceCube Neutrino Observatory, is at the Amundsen-Scott Station.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] It consists of around 5,500 digital optical modules, some of which reach a depth of 2,450 m (8,040 ft), that are held in 1 km3 (0.24 cu mi) of ice.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Scientists also observed higher radiation dose rates around the coast of Antarctica compared with the global average: this is attributed to cosmic rays going through the thinner atmosphere compared to equatorial latitudes.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Antarctica provides a unique environment for the study of meteorites: the dry polar desert preserves them well, and meteorites older than a million years have been found.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] They are relatively easy to find, as the dark stone meteorites stand out in a landscape of ice and snow, and the flow of ice accumulates them in certain areas.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Adelie Land meteorite, discovered in 1912, was the first to be found.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Meteorites contain clues about the composition of the Solar System and its early development.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Most meteorites come from asteroids, but a few meteorites found in Antarctica came from the Moon and Mars.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The first motion-picture footage of Antarctica is thought to have been hand-cranked by a unknown member of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition in early 1904.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Among the fiction films shot partly or entirely in Antarctica are *Mr.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Forbush and the Penguins*, a 1971 British comedy starring John Hurt; *Antarctica*, a 1983 Japanese survival drama with music by Vangelis; and *South of Sanity*, a 2012 low-budget British horror.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The Winter International Film Festival of Antarctica (WIFFA), established in 2006 as a way to combat social isolation, is held annually for those wintering on the continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] WIFFA is open to short films of 5 minutes or less, shot during a 48-hour window.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The southernmost music festival in the world, Icestock, has been held at McMurdo Station since 1989.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] The organizers, performers, and attendees of Icestock are all personnel working at McMurdo or nearby Scott Base.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Sporting events held on Antarctica include the Antarctic Ice Marathon & 100k ultra race, Antarctica Marathon and Antarctica Cup Yacht Race.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] Association football has been played since the early twentieth century, with teams representing bases or visiting ships.
[src:antarctica-novel/antarctica] There are two principal holidays celebrated across Antarctica: Midwinter Day on the day of the southern winter solstice (June 20 or 21) and Antarctica Day on December 1, which commemorates the signing of the Antarctic Treaty in 1959.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] A generation ship is launched from Earth in 2545 at 0.1 c (i.e. traveling at 30,000 km/s or 10% the speed of light).
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] It includes twenty-four self-contained biomes and an average population of two thousand people.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] One hundred sixty years and approximately seven generations later, it is beginning its deceleration into the Tau Ceti system to begin colonization of a planet's moon, an Earth analog, which has been named Aurora.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Devi, the ship's *de facto* chief engineer and leader, is concerned about the decaying infrastructure and biology of the ship: systems are breaking down, each generation has lower intelligence test scores than the last, and bacteria are mutating and evolving at a faster rate than humans.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] She tells the ship's AI, referred to simply as Ship, to keep a narrative of the voyage.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] After having some trouble with understanding the human concept of narrative, Ship eventually elects to follow the life of Devi's daughter Freya as a protagonist.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] As a teenager, Freya travels around the ship on her *Wanderjahr* and learns that many of the ship's inhabitants are dissatisfied with their enclosed existence and what they perceive as a dictatorship.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Movement is strictly limited for most people, reproduction is tightly controlled, and education in science and mathematics is mandatory.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Freya's *Wanderjahr* comes to an end when she is called home as Devi grows sick from cancer and dies.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] The ship arrives in the Tau Ceti system and begins to settle Aurora, a moon of Tau Ceti e.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] It soon becomes apparent that extraterrestrial life is present in the form of complex prions, which infect and kill some of the landing party.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] All except one of the remaining settlers attempts to return to the ship, and some of those remaining onboard kill them in the airlock to maintain quarantine, leading to a violent political schism throughout the ship.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] The ship itself, which has been moving towards self-awareness, takes physical control of the situation by lowering oxygen levels and separating warring factions, referring to itself as "the rule of law".
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] It then reveals to the crew that there were in fact two ships originally launched for the Tau Ceti expedition, but the other was destroyed during a period of severe civil unrest, and the collective memory of that event was erased from the history records.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Under Ship's moderation, a more peaceful debate takes place between the inhabitants about what to do now that Aurora is known to be inhospitable.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Unable to reach consensus, the factions agree to part ways, with those who wish to stay retaining as many resources as can be spared to pursue an unlikely attempt at terraforming the Mars-like moon Iris, while the other group, led by Freya, opts to try and return to Earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Using raw materials in the Tau Ceti system, they refuel the ship to allow acceleration back to Earth; since they lack fuel to decelerate, they must rely on the laser propulsion system that originally launched them from the Solar System to slow them down on approach.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] The last remaining Aurora settler, Jochi, who remains permanently quarantined in his shuttle attached to the exterior of the ship, elects to return to Earth as well.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Initially, Freya and the others who return remain in communication with those who remained in the Tau Ceti system, but much later on their voyage home this communication stops.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] On the voyage back to Earth, the ship's biomes continue to deteriorate as bacteria flourish and crops fail.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] The humans soon face famine and experiment with an untested form of cryogenic freezing, which is largely successful.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] The ship's repeated entreaties to Earth to turn back on the laser propulsion system are ignored due to societal and political strife back in the Solar System, and many citizens' anger at the colonists' "cowardice".
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Eventually a private group funds and reactivates the laser, but the delay means the ship's speed is only reduced by a fraction of what is needed.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Ship is therefore forced to decelerate by means of gravity assist between various planets, a process which takes twelve years.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] During this time, with the full communications data of humanity available to it, it learns more about why it was launched in the first place—simply for expansionism—and denounces its builders as "criminally negligent narcissists".
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] The ship manages to safely drop its humans off on a pass of Earth but fails to make a final gravity slowdown past the Sun.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Ship is destroyed, along with Jochi in his quarantined shuttle.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Freya and the other "starfarers" have trouble adjusting to life on Earth, especially with many Terrans hostile to them for a perceived sense of ingratitude and cowardice.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] At a space colonization conference, a speaker says humanity will continue to send ships into interstellar space no matter how many people fail and die, and Freya assaults him.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Eventually, she joins a group of terraformers who are attempting to restore the Earth's beaches after their loss during previous centuries' sea level rise.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] While swimming and surfing, she begins to come to terms with life on Earth.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Major themes in *Aurora* include the complexities of life aboard a multigenerational starship, interpersonal psychology, artificial intelligence, human migration, environmentalism, and the feasibility of interstellar travel.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] In researching the novel, Robinson met with his friend Christopher McKay, an American scientist who had been advising him since Robinson's *Mars Trilogy*.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] McKay arranged lunch meetings at the NASA Ames Research Center, where Robinson posed questions to NASA employees.
[src:antarctica-novel/aurora-novel] Writing in *The Guardian*, Adam Roberts described it as "the best generation starship novel I have ever read".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Prior to European colonization, California was one of the most culturally and linguistically diverse areas in pre-Columbian North America.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] European exploration in the 16th and 17th centuries led to the colonization by the Spanish Empire.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The area became a part of Mexico in 1821, as a result of its successful war for independence.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Following the U.S. conquest of California, part of the Mexican-American War, California was ceded to the United States in 1848.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The California gold rush started in 1848 and led to social and demographic changes, including the California genocide.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] It organized itself and was admitted as the 31st state in 1850 as a free state, following the Compromise of 1850.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Greater Los Angeles, the Inland Empire, and the San Francisco Bay Area are the nation's second, twelfth, and thirteenth most populous metropolitan areas.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Los Angeles is the state's most populous city and is ranked second in population in the nation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Part of the Californias region of North America, the state's diverse geography ranges from the Pacific Coast and metropolitan areas in the west to the Sierra Nevada mountains in the east, and from the redwood and Douglas fir forests in the northwest to the Mojave Desert in the southeast.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Two-thirds of the nation's earthquake risk lies in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Central Valley, a fertile agricultural area, dominates the state's center.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The large size of the state results in climates that vary from moist temperate rainforest in the north to arid desert in the interior, as well as snowy alpine in the mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] While California is warming and drying overall, with frequent wildfires, the state is also experiencing increasing weather whiplash.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The economy of California is the largest of any U.S. state, with an estimated 2025 gross state product of $4.296 trillion as of Q3 2025.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] It is also the world's largest sub-national economy and, if it were an independent country, would be the fourth-largest economy in the world (behind Germany and ahead of Japan) by nominal GDP as of 2025.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The state's agricultural industry leads the nation in output, fueled by its production of dairy, almonds, and grapes.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Despite heavy reliance on seaborne foreign crude oil, California also refines some of its own oil, primarily drilled from Kern County.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] With the busiest port in the country (Los Angeles), California plays a pivotal role in the global supply chain, hauling in about 40% of goods imported to the US.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Notable contributions to popular culture, ranging from entertainment, sports, music, and fashion, have their origins in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Despite an exodus of filmmaking from California, Hollywood continues to be an important center of the U.S. film industry, one of the oldest and largest film industries in the world; profoundly influencing global entertainment since the 1920s.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The San Francisco Bay Area's Silicon Valley is the center of the global technology industry.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Spaniards gave the name *Las Californias* to the peninsula of Baja California (in modern-day Mexico).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] As Spanish explorers and settlers moved north and inland, the region known as "California", or "Las Californias", grew in both area and population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Eventually it included lands north of the peninsula, Alta California, part of which became the present-day U.S. state of California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] A 2017 state legislative document stated, "Numerous theories exist as to the origin and meaning of the word 'California'", and that all anyone knows is the name was added to a map by 1541 "presumably by a Spanish navigator".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The name is most likely derived from the mythical island of California in the fictional story of Queen Calafia, as recorded in a 1510 work *The Adventures of Esplandián* by Garci Rodríguez de Montalvo.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Queen Calafia's kingdom was said to be a remote land rich in gold and pearls, inhabited by beautiful dark-skinned women who wore gold armor and lived like Amazons, and bred griffins for war.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Abbreviations of the state's name include CA, Cal, Calif, and US-CA.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] California was one of the most culturally and linguistically diverse areas in pre-Columbian North America.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Historians generally agree that there were at least 300,000 people living in California prior to European colonization.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Indigenous peoples of California included more than 70 distinct ethnic groups, inhabiting environments ranging from mountains and deserts to islands and redwood forests.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Living in these diverse geographic areas, the indigenous peoples developed complex forms of ecosystem management, including forest gardening to ensure the regular availability of important food sources and medicinal plants.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] This was a form of sustainable agriculture.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] To mitigate destructive large wildfires from ravaging the natural environment, indigenous peoples developed a practice of controlled burning.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] This practice was recognized for its benefits by the California government in 2022.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] These groups were also diverse in their political organization, with bands, tribes, villages, and, on the resource-rich coasts, large chiefdoms, such as the Chumash, Pomo and Salinan.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Trade, intermarriage, craft specialists, and military alliances fostered social and economic relationships between many groups.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Although nations would sometimes war, most armed conflicts were between groups of men for vengeance.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Acquiring territory was not usually the purpose of these small-scale battles.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Men and women generally had different roles in society.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Women were often responsible for weaving, harvesting, processing, and preparing food, while men for hunting and other forms of physical labor.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Most societies also had roles for people whom the Spanish referred to as *joyas*, who they saw as "men who dressed as women".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] *Joyas* were responsible for death, burial, and mourning rituals, and they performed women's social roles.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Indigenous societies had terms such as two-spirit to refer to them.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Chumash referred to them as *'aqi.* The early Spanish settlers detested and sought to eliminate them.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The first Europeans to explore the coast of California were the members of a Spanish maritime expedition led by Portuguese captain Juan Rodríguez Cabrillo in 1542.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Cabrillo was commissioned by Antonio de Mendoza, the Viceroy of New Spain, to lead an expedition up the Pacific coast in search of trade opportunities; they entered San Diego Bay on September 28, 1542, and reached at least as far north as San Miguel Island.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Privateer and explorer Francis Drake explored and claimed an undefined portion of the California coast in 1579, landing north of the future city of San Francisco.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The first documented Asians to set foot on what is now the United States occurred in 1587, when Filipino sailors arrived in Spanish ships at Morro Bay.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Descendants of the Islamic Caliph Hasan ibn Ali, who had been living in formerly Muslim Manila, transited through California while traveling to Guerrero, Mexico.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] These individuals, who had converted to Christianity while retaining some Islamic traditions, later played a role in Mexico's wars of independence.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Sebastián Vizcaíno explored and mapped the coast of California in 1602 for New Spain, putting ashore in Monterey.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Despite the on-the-ground explorations of California in the 16th century, Rodríguez's idea of California as an island persisted.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Such depictions appeared on many European maps well into the 18th century.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Portolá expedition of 1769–70 was a pivotal event in the Spanish colonization of California, resulting in the establishment of numerous missions, presidios, and pueblos.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The military and civil contingent of the expedition was led by Gaspar de Portolá, who traveled over land from Sonora into California, while the religious component was headed by Junípero Serra, who came by sea from Baja California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1769, Portolá and Serra established Mission San Diego de Alcalá and the Presidio of San Diego, the first religious and military settlements founded by the Spanish in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] By the end of the expedition in 1770, they would establish the Presidio of Monterey and Mission San Carlos Borromeo de Carmelo on Monterey Bay.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] After the Portolà expedition, Spanish missionaries led by Father-President Serra set out to establish 21 Spanish missions of California along El Camino Real ("The Royal Road") and along the California coast, 16 sites of which having been chosen during the Portolá expedition.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Numerous major cities in California grew out of missions, including San Francisco (Mission San Francisco de Asís), San Diego (Mission San Diego de Alcalá), Ventura (Mission San Buenaventura), and Santa Barbara (Mission Santa Barbara), among others.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Juan Bautista de Anza led a significant expedition throughout California in 1775–76, which would extend deeper into the interior and north of California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Anza expedition selected numerous sites for missions, presidios, and pueblos, which subsequently would be established by settlers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Gabriel Moraga, a member of the expedition, would also christen many of California's prominent rivers with their names in 1775–1776, such as the Sacramento River and the San Joaquin River.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] After the expedition, Gabriel's son, José Joaquín Moraga, founded the pueblo of San Jose in 1777, making it the first civilian-established city in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] During this same period, sailors from the Russian Empire explored along the northern coast of California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1812, the Russian-American Company established a trading post and small fortification at Fort Ross on the North Coast.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Fort Ross was primarily used to supply Russia's Alaskan colonies with food supplies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The settlement did not meet much success, failing to attract settlers or establish long term trade viability, and was abandoned by 1841.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] During the War of Mexican Independence, Alta California was largely unaffected and uninvolved in the revolution, though many Californios supported independence from Spain, which many believed had neglected California and limited its development.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Spain's trade monopoly on California had limited local trade prospects.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Following Mexican independence, California ports were freely able to trade with foreign merchants.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Governor Pablo Vicente de Solá presided over the transition from Spanish colonial rule to independent Mexican rule.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1821, the Mexican War of Independence gave the Mexican Empire (which included California) independence from Spain.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1822, the California's first legislature was formed, known as the Diputación de Alta California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The California mission system, which controlled much of the best land in Alta California, was secularized by 1834 and became the property of the Mexican government.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The governor granted many square leagues of land to others with political influence.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] These huge *ranchos* or cattle ranches emerged as the dominant institutions of Mexican California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The ranchos developed under ownership by Californios (Hispanics native of California) who traded cowhides and tallow with Boston merchants.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Beef did not become a commodity until the 1849 California Gold Rush.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] From the 1820s, trappers and settlers from the U.S. and Canada began to arrive in Northern California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] These new arrivals used the Siskiyou Trail, California Trail, Oregon Trail and Old Spanish Trail to cross the rugged mountains and harsh deserts in and surrounding California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The early government of the newly independent Mexico was highly unstable, and in a reflection of this, from 1831 onwards, California also experienced a series of armed disputes, both internal and with the central Mexican government.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] During this tumultuous political period Juan Bautista Alvarado was able to secure the governorship during 1836–1842.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The military action which first brought Alvarado to power had momentarily declared California to be an independent state, and had been aided by Anglo-American residents of California, including Isaac Graham.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1840, one hundred of those residents who did not have passports were arrested, leading to the Graham Affair, which was resolved in part with the intercession of Royal Navy officials.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] One of the largest ranchers in California was John Marsh.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] After failing to obtain justice against squatters on his land from the Mexican courts, he determined that California should become part of the United States.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Marsh conducted a letter-writing campaign espousing the California climate, the soil, and other reasons to settle there, as well as the best route to follow, which became known as "Marsh's route".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] His letters were read, reread, passed around, and printed in newspapers throughout the country, and started the first wagon trains rolling to California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] After ushering in the period of organized emigration to California, Marsh became involved in a military battle between the much-hated Mexican general, Manuel Micheltorena and the California governor he had replaced, Juan Bautista Alvarado.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] At the Battle of Providencia near Los Angeles, he convinced each side that they had no reason to be fighting each other.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] As a result of Marsh's actions, they abandoned the fight, Micheltorena was defeated, and California-born Pio Pico was returned to the governorship.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] This paved the way for California's ultimate acquisition by the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1846, a group of American settlers in and around Sonoma rebelled against Mexican rule during the Bear Flag Revolt.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Afterward, rebels raised the Bear Flag (featuring a bear, a star, a red stripe and the words "California Republic") at Sonoma.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The Republic's only president was William B.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Ide, who played a pivotal role during the Bear Flag Revolt.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] This revolt by American settlers served as a prelude to the later American military invasion of California and was closely coordinated with nearby American military commanders.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The California Republic was short-lived; the same year marked the outbreak of the Mexican–American War (1846–1848).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Navy sailed into Monterey Bay in 1846 and began the U.S. military invasion of California, with Northern California capitulating in less than a month to the U.S. forces.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In Southern California, Californios continued to resist American forces.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Notable military engagements of the conquest include the Battle of San Pasqual and the Battle of Dominguez Rancho in Southern California, as well as the Battle of Olómpali and the Battle of Santa Clara in Northern California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] After a series of defensive battles in the south, the Treaty of Cahuenga was signed by the Californios on January 13, 1847, securing a censure and establishing de facto American control in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The even more lightly populated and arid lower region of old Baja California remained as a part of Mexico.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1846, the total settler population of the western part of the old Alta California had been estimated to be no more than 8,000, plus about 100,000 Native Americans, down from about 300,000 before Hispanic settlement in 1769.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1848, gold was discovered at Sutter's Mill, just weeks prior to the formal transfer of California to the United States under the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] This monumental event triggered the California gold rush—one of the largest mass migrations in modern history.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The ensuing population boom permanently transformed the region's economy and demographics, as hundreds of thousands of fortune-seekers from the eastern United States, Europe, Latin America, and Asia flooded the territory.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] By the time of California's application for statehood in 1850, the settler population of California had multiplied to 100,000.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Between 1847 and 1870, the population of San Francisco increased from 500 to 150,000.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The seat of government for California under Spanish and later Mexican rule had been located in Monterey from 1777 until 1845.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Pio Pico, the last Mexican governor of Alta California, had briefly moved the capital to Los Angeles in 1845.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The U.S. consulate had also been located in Monterey, under consul Thomas O.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 1849, a state Constitutional Convention was first held in Monterey.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Among the first tasks of the convention was a decision on a location for the new state capital.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The first full legislative sessions were held in San Jose (1850–1851).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Subsequent locations included Vallejo (1852–1853), and nearby Benicia (1853–1854); these locations eventually proved to be inadequate as well.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The capital has been located in Sacramento since 1854 with only a short break in 1862 when legislative sessions were held in San Francisco due to flooding in Sacramento.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Once the state's Constitutional Convention had finalized its state constitution, it applied to the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] On September 9, 1850, as part of the Compromise of 1850, California became a free state and September 9 a state holiday.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), California sent gold shipments eastward to Washington in support of the Union.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] However, due to the existence of a large contingent of pro-South sympathizers within the state, the state was not able to muster any full military regiments to send eastwards to officially serve in the Union war effort.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Still, several smaller military units within the Union army, such as the "California 100 Company", were unofficially associated with the state of California due to a majority of their members being from California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] At the time of California's admission into the Union, travel between California and the rest of the continental U.S. had been a time-consuming and dangerous feat.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Nineteen years later, and seven years after it was greenlighted by President Lincoln, the first transcontinental railroad was completed in 1869.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] California was then reachable from the eastern States in a week's time.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Much of the state was well suited to fruit cultivation and agriculture in general.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Vast expanses of wheat, other cereal crops, vegetable crops, cotton, and nut and fruit trees were grown (including oranges in Southern California), and the foundation was laid for the state's prodigious agricultural production in the Central Valley and elsewhere.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In the nineteenth century, a large number of migrants from China traveled to the state as part of the gold rush or to seek work.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Under earlier Spanish and Mexican rule, California's original native population had precipitously declined, above all, from Eurasian diseases to which the Indigenous people of California had not yet developed a natural immunity.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Under its new American administration, California's first governor Peter Hardeman Burnett instituted policies that have been described as a state-sanctioned policy of elimination of California's indigenous people.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Burnett announced in 1851 in his Second Annual Message to the Legislature: "That a war of extermination will continue to be waged between the races until the Indian race becomes extinct must be expected.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] As in other American states, indigenous peoples were forcibly removed from their lands by American settlers, like miners, ranchers, and farmers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Although California had entered the American union as a free state, the "loitering or orphaned Indians", were *de facto* enslaved by their new Anglo-American masters under the 1850 *Act for the Government and Protection of Indians*.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] One of these *de facto* slave auctions was approved by the Los Angeles City Council and occurred for nearly twenty years.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] There were many massacres in which hundreds of indigenous people were killed by settlers for their land.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Between 1850 and 1860, the California state government paid around 1.5 million dollars (some 250,000 of which was reimbursed by the federal government) to hire militias with the stated purpose of protecting settlers, however these militias perpetrated numerous massacres of indigenous people.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Indigenous people were also forcibly moved to reservations and rancherias, which were often small and isolated and without enough natural resources or funding from the government to adequately sustain the populations living on them.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] As a result, settler colonialism was a calamity for indigenous people.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Several scholars and Native American activists, including Benjamin Madley and Ed Castillo, have described the actions of the California government as a genocide, as well as the 40th governor of California Gavin Newsom.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Benjamin Madley estimates that from 1846 to 1873, between 9,492 and 16,092 indigenous people were killed, including between 1,680 and 3,741 killed by the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In the 20th century, thousands of Japanese people migrated to California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The state in 1913 passed the Alien Land Act, excluding Asian immigrants from owning land.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] During World War II, Japanese Americans in California were interned in concentration camps; in 2020, California apologized.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Migration to California accelerated during the early 20th century with the completion of transcontinental highways like the Route 66.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] From 1900 to 1965, the population grew from fewer than one million to the greatest in the Union.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Census Bureau reported California's population as 6% Hispanic, 2.4% Asian, and 90% non-Hispanic white.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] To meet the population's needs, engineering feats like the California and Los Angeles Aqueducts; the Oroville and Shasta Dams; and the Bay and Golden Gate Bridges were built.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The state government adopted the California Master Plan for Higher Education in 1960 to develop an efficient system of public education.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Meanwhile, attracted to the mild Mediterranean climate, cheap land, and the state's variety of geography, filmmakers established the studio system in Hollywood in the 1920s.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] California manufactured 9% of U.S. armaments produced during World War II, ranking third behind New York and Michigan.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] California easily ranked first in production of military ships at drydock facilities in San Diego, Los Angeles, and the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Due to the hiring opportunities California offered during the conflict, the population multiplied from the immigration it received due to the work in its war factories, military bases, and training facilities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] After World War II, California's economy expanded due to strong aerospace and defense industries, whose size decreased following the end of the Cold War.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Stanford University began encouraging faculty and graduates to stay instead of leaving the state, and develop a high-tech region, now known as Silicon Valley.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] As a result of this, California is a world center of the entertainment and music industries, of technology, engineering, and the aerospace industry, and as the U.S. center of agricultural production.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Just before the Dot Com Bust, California had the fifth-largest economy in the world.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In the mid and late twentieth century, race-related incidents occurred.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Tensions between police and African Americans, combined with unemployment and poverty in inner cities, led to riots, such as the 1992 Rodney King riots.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] California was the hub of the Black Panther Party, known for arming African Americans to defend against racial injustice.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Mexican, Filipino, and other migrant farm workers rallied in the state around Cesar Chavez for better pay in the 1960s and 70s.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] During the 20th century, two great disasters happened: the 1906 San Francisco earthquake and 1928 St.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Francis Dam flood remain the deadliest in U.S. history.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Although air pollution has been reduced, health problems associated with pollution continue.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Brown haze known as "smog" has been substantially abated after federal and state restrictions on automobile exhaust.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] An energy crisis in 2001 led to rolling blackouts, soaring power rates, and the importation of electricity from neighboring states.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Southern California Edison and Pacific Gas and Electric Company came under heavy criticism.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Housing prices in urban areas continued to increase; a modest home which in the 1960s cost $25,000 would cost half a million dollars or more in urban areas by 2005.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] More people commuted longer hours to afford a home in more rural areas while earning larger salaries in the urban areas.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Speculators bought houses, expecting to make a huge profit in months, then rolling it over by buying more properties.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Mortgage companies were compliant, as people assumed prices would keep rising.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The bubble burst in 2007–2008 as prices began to crash.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Hundreds of billions in property values vanished and foreclosures soared, as financial institutions and investors were badly hurt.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In the 21st century, droughts and frequent wildfires attributed to climate change have occurred.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] From 2011 to 2017, a persistent drought was the worst in its recorded history.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] The 2018 wildfire season was the state's deadliest and most destructive.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] One of the first confirmed COVID-19 cases in the U.S. occurred in California on January 26, 2020.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] A state of emergency was declared in the state on March 4, 2020, and remained in effect until Governor Gavin Newsom ended it in February 2023.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] A mandatory statewide stay-at-home order was issued on March 19, 2020, which was ended in January 2021.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Cultural and language revitalization efforts among indigenous Californians have progressed among tribes as of 2022.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] Some land returns to indigenous stewardship have occurred.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p01] In 2022, the largest dam removal and river restoration project in U.S. history was announced for the Klamath River, as a win for California tribes.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Covering an area of 163,696 sq mi (423,970 km2), California is the third-largest state in the U.S. in area, after Alaska and Texas.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California is one of the most geographically diverse states in the union and is often geographically bisected into two regions, Southern California, comprising the ten southernmost counties, and Northern California, comprising the 48 northernmost counties.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In the middle of the state lies the California Central Valley, bounded by the Sierra Nevada in the east, the coastal mountain ranges in the west, the Cascade Range to the north and by the Tehachapi Mountains in the south.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Central Valley is California's productive agricultural heartland.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Divided in two by the Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta, the northern portion, the Sacramento Valley serves as the watershed of the Sacramento River, while the southern portion, the San Joaquin Valley is the watershed for the San Joaquin River.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Both valleys derive their names from the rivers that flow through them.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] With dredging, the Sacramento and the San Joaquin Rivers have remained deep enough for several inland cities to be seaports.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta is a critical water supply hub for the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Water is diverted from the delta and through an extensive network of pumps and canals that traverse nearly the length of the state, to the Central Valley and the State Water Projects and other needs.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Water from the Delta provides drinking water for nearly 23 million people, almost two-thirds of the state's population as well as water for farmers on the west side of the San Joaquin Valley.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Suisun Bay lies at the confluence of the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The water is drained by the Carquinez Strait, which flows into San Pablo Bay, a northern extension of San Francisco Bay, which then connects to the Pacific Ocean via the Golden Gate strait.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Channel Islands are located off the Southern coast, while the Farallon Islands lie west of San Francisco.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Sierra Nevada (Spanish for "snowy range") includes the highest peak in the contiguous 48 states, Mount Whitney, at 14,505 feet (4,421 m).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The range embraces Yosemite Valley, famous for its glacially carved domes, and Sequoia National Park, home to the giant sequoia trees, the largest living organisms on Earth, and the deep freshwater lake, Lake Tahoe, the largest lake in the state by volume.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] To the east of the Sierra Nevada are Owens Valley and Mono Lake, an essential migratory bird habitat.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In the western part of the state is Clear Lake, the largest freshwater lake by area entirely in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Although Lake Tahoe is larger, it is divided by the California/Nevada border.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Sierra Nevada falls to Arctic temperatures in winter and has several dozen small glaciers, including Palisade Glacier, the southernmost glacier in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Tulare Lake was the largest freshwater lake west of the Mississippi River.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] A remnant of Pleistocene-era Lake Corcoran, Tulare Lake dried up by the early 20th century after its tributary rivers were diverted for agricultural irrigation and municipal water uses.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] About 45% of the state's total surface area is covered by forests, and California's diversity of pine species is unmatched by any other state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California contains more forestland than any other state except Alaska.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Many of the trees in the California White Mountains are the oldest in the world; an individual bristlecone pine is over 5,000 years old.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In the south is a large inland salt lake, the Salton Sea.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The south-central desert is called the Mojave; to the northeast of the Mojave lies Death Valley, which contains the lowest and hottest place in North America, the Badwater Basin at −279 feet (−85 m).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The horizontal distance from the bottom of Death Valley to the top of Mount Whitney is less than 90 miles (140 km).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Indeed, almost all of southeastern California is arid, hot desert, with routine extreme high temperatures during the summer.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The southeastern border of California with Arizona is entirely formed by the Colorado River, from which the southern part of the state gets about half of its water.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] A majority of California's cities are located in either the San Francisco Bay Area or the Sacramento metropolitan area in Northern California; or the Los Angeles area, the Inland Empire, or the San Diego metropolitan area in Southern California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Los Angeles Area, the Bay Area, and the San Diego metropolitan area are among several major metropolitan areas along the California coast.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As part of the Ring of Fire, California is subject to tsunamis, floods, droughts, Santa Ana winds, wildfires, and landslides on steep terrain; California also has several volcanoes.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] It has many earthquakes due to several faults running through the state, the largest being the San Andreas Fault.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] About 37,000 earthquakes are recorded each year; most are too small to be felt.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Among Americans at risk of serious harm from a major earthquake, two-thirds of that population are residents of California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Most of the state has a Mediterranean climate.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The cool California Current offshore often creates summer fog near the coast.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Farther inland, there are colder winters and hotter summers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The maritime moderation results in the shoreline summertime temperatures of Los Angeles and San Francisco being the coolest of all major metropolitan areas of the U.S. and uniquely cool compared to areas on the same latitude in the interior and on the east coast of the North American continent.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Even the San Diego shoreline bordering Mexico is cooler in summer than most areas in the contiguous U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Just a few miles inland, summer temperature extremes are significantly higher, with downtown Los Angeles being several degrees warmer than at the coast.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The same microclimate phenomenon is seen in the climate of the Bay Area, where areas sheltered from the ocean experience significantly hotter summers and colder winters in contrast with nearby areas closer to the ocean.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Northern parts of the state have more rain than the south.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California's mountain ranges also influence the climate: some of the rainiest parts of the state are west-facing mountain slopes.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Coastal northwestern California has a temperate climate, and the Central Valley has a Mediterranean climate but with greater temperature extremes than the coast.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The high mountains, including the Sierra Nevada, have an alpine climate with snow in winter and mild to moderate heat in summer.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California's mountains produce rain shadows on the eastern side, creating extensive deserts.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The higher elevation deserts of eastern California have hot summers and cold winters, while the low deserts east of the Southern California mountains have hot summers and nearly frostless mild winters.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Death Valley, a desert with large expanses below sea level, is considered the hottest location in the world; the highest temperature in the world, 134 °F (56.7 °C), was recorded there on July 10, 1913.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The lowest temperature in California was −45 °F (−43 °C) on January 20, 1937, in Boca.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The table below lists average temperatures for January and August in a selection of places throughout the state; some highly populated and some not.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] This includes the relatively cool summers of the Humboldt Bay region around Eureka, the extreme heat of Death Valley, and the mountain climate of Mammoth in the Sierra Nevada.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The wide range of climates leads to a high demand for water.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Over time, droughts have been increasing due to climate change and overextraction, becoming less seasonal and more year-round, further straining California's electricity supply and water security and having an impact on California business, industry, and agriculture.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In 2022, a new state program was created in collaboration with indigenous peoples of California to revive the practice of controlled burns as a way of clearing excessive forest debris and making landscapes more resilient to wildfires.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Native American use of fire in ecosystem management was outlawed in 1911, yet has now been recognized.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California is one of the ecologically richest and most diverse parts of the world, and includes some of the most endangered ecological communities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California is part of the Nearctic realm and spans a number of terrestrial ecoregions.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California's large number of endemic species includes relict species, which have died out elsewhere, such as the Catalina ironwood (*Lyonothamnus floribundus*).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Many other endemics originated through differentiation or adaptive radiation, whereby multiple species develop from a common ancestor to take advantage of diverse ecological conditions such as the California lilac (*Ceanothus*).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Many California endemics have become endangered, as urbanization, logging, overgrazing, and the introduction of exotic species have encroached on their habitat.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California boasts several superlatives in its collection of flora: the largest trees, the tallest trees, and the oldest trees.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California's native grasses are perennial plants, and there are close to hundred succulent species native to the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] After European contact, these were generally replaced by invasive species of European annual grasses; and, in modern times, California's hills turn a characteristic golden-brown in summer.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Plant life in the dry climate of the lower Sonoran zone contains a diversity of native cactus, mesquite, and paloverde.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Joshua tree is found in the Mojave Desert.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Flowering plants include the dwarf desert poppy and a variety of asters.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Fremont cottonwood and valley oak thrive in the Central Valley.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The upper Sonoran zone includes the chaparral belt, characterized by forests of small shrubs, stunted trees, and herbaceous plants.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] *Nemophila*, mint, *Phacelia*, *Viola*, and the California poppy (*Eschscholzia californica*, the state flower) also flourish in this zone, along with the lupine, more species of which occur here than anywhere else in the world.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The transition zone includes most of California's forests with the redwood (*Sequoia sempervirens*) and the "big tree" or giant sequoia (*Sequoiadendron giganteum*), among the oldest living things on earth (some are said to have lived at least 4,000 years).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Tanbark oak, California laurel, sugar pine, madrona, broad-leaved maple, and Douglas-fir also grow here.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Forest floors are covered with swordfern, alumnroot, barrenwort, and trillium, and there are thickets of huckleberry, azalea, elder, and wild currant.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Characteristic wild flowers include varieties of mariposa, tulip, and tiger and leopard lilies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The high elevations of the Canadian zone allow the Jeffrey pine, red fir, and lodgepole pine to thrive.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Brushy areas are abundant with dwarf manzanita and ceanothus; the unique Sierra puffball is also found here.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Right below the timberline, in the Hudsonian zone, the whitebark, foxtail, and silver pines grow.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] At about 10,500 feet (3,200 m), begins the Arctic zone, a treeless region whose flora include a number of wildflowers, including Sierra primrose, yellow columbine, alpine buttercup, and alpine shooting star.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Palm trees are a well-known feature of California, particularly in Southern California and Los Angeles; many species have been imported, though the *Washington filifera* (commonly known as the *California fan palm*) is native to the state, mainly growing in the Colorado Desert oases.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Other common plants that have been introduced to the state include the eucalyptus, acacia, pepper tree, geranium, and Scotch broom.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The species that are federally classified as endangered are the Contra Costa wallflower, Antioch Dunes evening primrose, Solano grass, San Clemente Island larkspur, salt marsh bird's beak, McDonald's rock-cress, and Santa Barbara Island liveforever.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of December 1997, 85 plant species were listed as threatened or endangered.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In the deserts of the lower Sonoran zone, the mammals include the jackrabbit, kangaroo rat, squirrel, and opossum.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Common birds include the owl, roadrunner, cactus wren, and various species of hawk.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The area's reptilian life include the sidewinder viper, desert tortoise, and horned toad.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The upper Sonoran zone boasts mammals such as the antelope, brown-footed woodrat, and ring-tailed cat.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Birds unique to this zone are the California thrasher, bushtit, and California condor.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In the transition zone, there are Colombian black-tailed deer, black bears, gray foxes, cougars, bobcats, and Roosevelt elk.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Reptiles such as the garter snakes and rattlesnakes inhabit the zone.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In addition, amphibians such as the water puppy and redwood salamander are common too.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Birds such as the kingfisher, chickadee, towhee, and hummingbird thrive here as well.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Canadian zone mammals include the mountain weasel, snowshoe hare, and several species of chipmunks.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Conspicuous birds include the blue-fronted jay, mountain chickadee, hermit thrush, American dipper, and Townsend's solitaire.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As one ascends into the Hudsonian zone, birds become scarcer.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] While the gray-crowned rosy finch is the only bird native to the high Arctic region, other bird species such as Anna's hummingbird and Clark's nutcracker.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Principal mammals found in this region include the Sierra coney, white-tailed jackrabbit, and the bighorn sheep.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of April 2003, the bighorn sheep was listed as endangered by the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The fauna found throughout several zones are the mule deer, coyote, mountain lion, northern flicker, and several species of hawk and sparrow.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Aquatic life in California thrives, from the state's mountain lakes and streams to the rocky Pacific coastline.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Numerous trout species are found, among them rainbow, golden, and cutthroat.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Migratory species of salmon are common as well.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Deep-sea life forms include sea bass, yellowfin tuna, barracuda, and several types of whale.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Native to the cliffs of northern California are seals, sea lions, and many types of shorebirds, including migratory species.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of April 2003, 118 California animals were on the federal endangered list; 181 plants were listed as endangered or threatened.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Eleven butterflies are also endangered and two that are threatened are on the federal list.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Among threatened animals are the coastal California gnatcatcher, Paiute cutthroat trout, southern sea otter, and northern spotted owl.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California has a total of 290,821 acres (1,176.91 km2) of National Wildlife Refuges.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of September 2010, 123 California animals were listed as either endangered or threatened on the federal list.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Also, as of the same year, 178 species of California plants were listed either as endangered or threatened on this federal list.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The most prominent river system within California is formed by the Sacramento River and San Joaquin River, which are fed mostly by snowmelt from the west slope of the Sierra Nevada, and respectively drain the north and south halves of the Central Valley.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The two rivers join in the Sacramento–San Joaquin River Delta, flowing into the Pacific Ocean through San Francisco Bay.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Many major tributaries feed into the Sacramento–San Joaquin system, including the Pit River, Feather River and Tuolumne River.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Klamath and Trinity Rivers drain a large area in far northwestern California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Eel River and Salinas River each drain portions of the California coast, north and south of San Francisco Bay, respectively.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Mojave River is the primary watercourse in the Mojave Desert, and the Santa Ana River drains much of the Transverse Ranges as it bisects Southern California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Colorado River forms the state's southeast border with Arizona.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Most of California's major rivers are dammed as part of two massive water projects: the Central Valley Project, providing water for agriculture in the Central Valley, and the California State Water Project diverting water from Northern to Southern California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The state's coasts, rivers, and other bodies of water are regulated by the California Coastal Commission.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California is traditionally separated into Northern California and Southern California, divided by a straight border which runs across the state, separating the northern 48 counties from the southern 10 counties.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Despite the persistence of the northern-southern divide, California is more precisely divided into many regions, multiple of which stretch across the northern-southern divide.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The state has 483 incorporated cities and towns, of which 461 are cities and 22 are towns.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Under California law, the terms "city" and "town" are explicitly interchangeable; the name of an incorporated municipality in the state can either be "City of (Name)" or "Town of (Name)".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Sacramento became California's first incorporated city on February 27, 1850.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] San Jose, San Diego, and Benicia tied for California's second incorporated city, each receiving incorporation on March 27, 1850.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Mountain House became the state's most recent and 483rd incorporated municipality on July 1, 2024.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The majority of these cities and towns are within one of five metropolitan areas: the Los Angeles Metropolitan Area, the San Francisco Bay Area, the Riverside-San Bernardino Area, the San Diego metropolitan area, or the Sacramento metropolitan area.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Presently, close to one out of every nine U.S. residents live in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] According to the 2020 U.S. census, the population of California was 39.54 million on April 1, 2020, a 6.13% increase since 2010.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] During that decade, the state's population grew more slowly than the rest of the nation, resulting in the loss of one seat on the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] House of Representatives, the first loss in its entire history.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The estimated state population in 2023 was 38.94 million.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] For well over a century (1900–2020), California experienced steady population growth.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Even while the rate of growth began to slow by the 1990s, some growth progressed into the first two decades of the 21st century; California added an average of around 400,000 people per year to its population during the period 1940–2020.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Then in 2020, the state began to experience population declines continuing every year, attributable mostly to moves out of state but also due to declining birth rates, COVID-19 pandemic deaths, and less internal migration from other states to California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Census Bureau, between 2021 and 2022, 818,000 California residents moved out of state with emigrants listing high cost of living, California housing shortage rise of remote work, high taxes, and a difficult business environment as the motivation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The net loss of population in California between July 2020 and July 2023 was 433,000.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of the 2020 Census, California had a population density of 250/mi2 and a population-weighted density of 7954/mi2.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Greater Los Angeles Area is the second-largest metropolitan area in the U.S., while Los Angeles is the second-largest city in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Los Angeles County has held the title of most populous U.S. county for decades and it alone is more populous than 42 U.S. states.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] San Francisco is the most densely populated city in California and one of the most densely populated cities in the U.S..
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Four of the top 20 most populous cities in the U.S. are in California: Los Angeles (2nd), San Diego (8th), San Jose (13th), and San Francisco (17th).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The center of population of California is located four miles west-southwest of the city of Shafter, Kern County.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of 2020, California ranked fourth among states by life expectancy, with a life expectancy of 79.0 years.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Starting in 2010, for the first time since the California Gold Rush, California-born residents made up the majority of the state's population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Along with the rest of the U.S., California's immigration pattern has also shifted over the course of the late 2000s to early 2010s.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Immigration from Latin American countries has dropped significantly with most immigrants now coming from Asia.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In total for 2011, there were 277,304 immigrants; 57% came from Asian countries versus 22% from Latin American countries.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Net immigration from Mexico, previously the most common country of origin for new immigrants, has dropped to zero / less than zero since more Mexican nationals are departing for their home country than immigrating.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The state's population of undocumented immigrants has been shrinking in recent years, due to increased enforcement and decreased job opportunities for lower-skilled workers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The number of migrants arrested attempting to cross the Mexican border in the Southwest decreased from a high of 1.1 million in 2005 to 367,000 in 2011.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Despite these recent trends, undocumented immigrants constituted an estimated 7.3% of the state's population, the third highest percentage of any state in the country, totaling nearly 2.6 million.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In particular, illegal immigrants tended to be concentrated in Los Angeles, Monterey, San Benito, Imperial, and Napa Counties—the latter four of which have significant agricultural industries that depend on manual labor.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] More than half of illegal immigrants originate from Mexico.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The state of California and some California cities, including Los Angeles, Oakland, and San Francisco, have adopted sanctuary policies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 171,521 homeless people in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] These numbers add up to more than 100% because respondents can select multiple racial identities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] 19% of Californians identified as two or more races in 2022, although excluding respondents who selected "some other race", only 5% identified as two or more races.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] By ethnicity, in 2018 the population was 60.7% non-Hispanic (of any race) and 39.3% Hispanic or Latino (of any race).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Hispanics are the largest single ethnic group in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Non-Hispanic whites constituted 36.8% of the state's population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] *Californios* are the Hispanic residents native to California, who make up the Spanish-speaking community that has existed in California since 1542, of varying Mexican American/Chicano, Criollo Spaniard, and Mestizo origin.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] However, they make up only a small part of California's Hispanic population today, estimated at 500,000.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California has the largest Mexican, Salvadoran, and Guatemalan populations in the U.S., together making up over 90% of the state's Latino population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As of 2011, 75.1% of California's population younger than age 1 were minorities, meaning they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic white (white Hispanics are counted as minorities).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In terms of total numbers, California has the largest population of White Americans in the U.S., an estimated 22,200,000 residents including people identifying as white in combination with any other race.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The state has the 5th largest population of African Americans in the U.S., an estimated 2,250,000 residents.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California's Asian American population is estimated at 7.1 million, constituting a third of the nation's total.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California's Native American population of 504,000 is the most of any state, with 103,030 identifying as Non-Hispanic and belonging mostly to the Indigenous peoples of California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Most of the state's Native American population identifies as Hispanic and belongs to Indigenous Mexican or Central American ethnic groups, including 185,200 identifying as Mexican American Indian and 67,904 identifying as Central American Indian.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] According to estimates from 2011, California has the largest minority population in the U.S. by numbers, making up 60% of the state population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Over the past 25 years, the population of non-Hispanic whites has declined, while Hispanic and Asian populations have grown.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Between 1970 and 2011, non-Hispanic whites declined from 80% of the state's population to 40%, while Hispanics grew from 32% in 2000 to 38% in 2011.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] It is currently projected that Hispanics will rise to 49% of the population by 2060, primarily due to domestic births rather than immigration.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] With the decline of immigration from Latin America, Asian Americans now constitute the fastest growing racial/ethnic group in California; this growth is primarily driven by immigration from China, India, and the Philippines, respectively.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The majority of California's immigrants were born in Latin America (49%) or Asia (41%).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] English serves as California's de jure and de facto official language.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] According to the 2021 American Community Survey conducted by the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Census Bureau, 56.08% (20,763,638) of California residents age 5 and older spoke only English at home, while 43.92% spoke another language at home.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Some 60.35% of California residents who speak a language other than English at home are able to speak English "well" or "very well", with this figure varying significantly across the different linguistic groups.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Like most U.S. states (32 out of 50), California law enshrines English as its official language, and has done so since the passage of Proposition 63 by California voters in 1986.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Various government agencies do, and are often required to, furnish documents in the various languages needed to reach their intended audiences.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Spanish is the most commonly spoken language in California behind English, spoken by 28.18% (10,434,308) of the state's population in 2021.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The Spanish language has been spoken in California since 1542 and is deeply intertwined with California's cultural landscape and history.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Spanish was the official administrative language of California through the Spanish and Mexican eras, until 1848.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Conquest of California and the Treaty of Guadalupe-Hidalgo, the U.S. federal government guaranteed the rights of Spanish-speaking Californians.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The first Constitution of California was written in both languages at the Monterey Constitutional Convention of 1849 and protected the rights of Spanish speakers to use their language in government proceedings and mandating that all government documents be published in both English and Spanish.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Despite the initial recognition of Spanish by early American governments in California, the revised 1879 state constitution stripped the rights of Spanish speakers and the official status of Spanish.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The growth of the English-only movement by the mid-20th century led to the passage of 1986 California Proposition 63, which enshrined English as the only official language in California and ended Spanish as a language of instruction in public schools.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] 2016 California Proposition 58 reversed the prohibition on bilingual education, though there are still many barriers to the proliferation of Spanish bilingual education, including a shortage of teachers and lack of funding.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The government of California has since made efforts to promote Spanish language access and bilingual education, as have private educational institutions in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Many businesses in California promote Spanish language skills for their employees, to better serve both California's Hispanic population and the larger Spanish-speaking world.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California has historically been one of the most linguistically diverse areas in the world, with more than 70 indigenous languages derived from 64 root languages in six language families.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] A survey conducted between 2007 and 2009 identified 23 different indigenous languages among California farmworkers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] All of California's indigenous languages are endangered, although there are now efforts toward language revitalization.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California has the highest concentration nationwide of Chinese, Vietnamese and Punjabi speakers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] As a result of the state's increasing diversity and migration from other areas across the country and around the globe, linguists began noticing a noteworthy set of emerging characteristics of spoken American English in California since the late 20th century.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] This variety, known as California English, has a vowel shift and several other phonological processes that are different from varieties of American English used in other regions of the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The largest religious denominations by number of adherents as a percentage of California's population in 2014 were the Catholic Church with 28%, Evangelical Protestants with 20%, and Mainline Protestants with 10%.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Together, all kinds of Protestants accounted for 32%.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] Those unaffiliated with any religion represented 27% of the population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The breakdown of other religions is 1% Muslim, 2% Hindu and 2% Buddhist.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] This is a change from 2008, when the population identified their religion with the Catholic Church with 31%; Evangelical Protestants with 18%; and Mainline Protestants with 14%.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] In 2008, those unaffiliated with any religion represented 21% of the population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The breakdown of other religions in 2008 was 0.5% Muslim, 1% Hindu and 2% Buddhist.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The *American Jewish Year Book* placed the total Jewish population of California at about 1,194,190 in 2006.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA) the largest denominations by adherents in 2010 were the Catholic Church with 10,233,334; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 763,818; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 489,953.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California has a large Catholic population due to the large numbers of Mexicans and Central Americans living within its borders.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] California has twelve dioceses and two archdioceses, the Archdiocese of Los Angeles and the Archdiocese of San Francisco, the former being the largest archdiocese in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] A Pew Research Center survey revealed that California is somewhat less religious than the rest of the states: 62% of Californians say they are "absolutely certain" of their belief in God, while in the nation 71% say so.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p02] The survey also revealed 48% of Californians say religion is "very important", compared to 56% nationally.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The culture of California is a Western culture and has its modern roots in U.S. culture, but also, historically, many Hispanic Californio and Mexican influences.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As a border and coastal state, California culture has been greatly influenced by several large immigrant populations, especially those from Latin America and Asia.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has long been a subject of interest in the public mind and has often been promoted by its boosters as a kind of paradise.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In the early 20th century, fueled by the efforts of state, the building projects during the Great Depression and local boosters, many Americans saw the Golden State as an ideal resort destination, sunny and dry all year round with easy access to the ocean and mountains.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In the 1960s, popular music groups such as the Beach Boys promoted the image of Californians as laid-back, tanned beach-goers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Hollywood and the rest of the Los Angeles area is a major global center for entertainment, with the U.S. film industry's "Big Five" major film studios (Columbia, Disney, Paramount, Universal, and Warner Bros.) as well as many minor film studios being based in or around the area.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Many animation studios are also headquartered in the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The four major American television commercial broadcast networks (ABC, CBS, NBC, and Fox) as well as other networks all have production facilities and offices in the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] All the four major commercial broadcast networks, plus the two major Spanish-language networks (Telemundo and Univision) each have at least three owned-and-operated TV stations in California, including at least one in Los Angeles and at least one in San Francisco.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] One of the oldest radio stations in the U.S. still in existence, KCBS (AM) in the San Francisco Bay Area, was founded in 1909.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Universal Music Group, one of the "Big Four" record labels, is based in Santa Monica, while Warner Records is based in Los Angeles.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Many independent record labels, such as Mind of a Genius Records, are also headquartered in the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Other genres such as pop rock, indie rock, hard rock, hip hop, pop, rock, rockabilly, country, heavy metal, grunge, new wave and disco were popularized in the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In addition, many British bands, such as Led Zeppelin, Deep Purple, Black Sabbath, and the Rolling Stones settled in the state after becoming internationally famous.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As the home of Silicon Valley, the Bay Area is the headquarters of several prominent internet media, social media, and other technology companies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Three of the "Big Five" technology companies (Apple, Meta, and Google) are based in the area as well as other services such as Netflix, Pandora Radio, Twitter, Yahoo!, and YouTube.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Other prominent companies that are headquartered here include HP inc. and Intel.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Microsoft and Amazon also have offices in the area.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California, particularly Southern California, is considered the birthplace of modern car culture.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Several fast food, fast casual, and casual dining chains were also founded California, including some that have since expanded internationally like California Pizza Kitchen, Denny's, IHOP, McDonald's, Panda Express, and Taco Bell.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has 18 major professional sports league franchises, far more than any other state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The San Francisco Bay Area has five major league teams, while the Greater Los Angeles Area is home to ten.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] San Diego has two major league teams and Sacramento has one.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The NFL Super Bowl has been hosted in California 12 times at five different stadiums: Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, the Rose Bowl, Stanford Stadium, Levi's Stadium, and San Diego Stadium.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] A thirteenth, Super Bowl LVI, was held at SoFi Stadium in Inglewood on February 13, 2022.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has long had many respected collegiate sports programs.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California is home to the oldest college bowl game, the annual Rose Bowl, among others.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The NFL has three teams in the state: the Los Angeles Rams, Los Angeles Chargers, and San Francisco 49ers.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] MLB has four teams in the state: the San Francisco Giants, Los Angeles Dodgers, Los Angeles Angels, and San Diego Padres.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The NBA has four teams in the state: the Golden State Warriors, Los Angeles Clippers, Los Angeles Lakers, and Sacramento Kings.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Additionally, the WNBA also has two teams in the state: the Los Angeles Sparks and Golden State Valkyries.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The NHL has three teams in the state: the Anaheim Ducks, Los Angeles Kings, and San Jose Sharks.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] MLS has four teams in the state: the Los Angeles Galaxy, San Jose Earthquakes, Los Angeles FC, and San Diego FC.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] MLR has one team in the state: the San Diego Legion.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California is the only U.S. state to have hosted both the Summer and Winter Olympics.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The 1932 and 1984 summer games were held in Los Angeles.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Squaw Valley Ski Resort (now Palisades Tahoe) in the Lake Tahoe region hosted the 1960 Winter Olympics.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Los Angeles will host the 2028 Summer Olympics, marking the fourth time that California will have hosted the Olympic Games.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Multiple games during the 1994 FIFA World Cup took place in California, with the Rose Bowl hosting eight matches (including the final), while Stanford Stadium hosted six matches.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The 2026 World Cup is scheduled to return in 2026, from June 11 to July 19.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] SoFi Stadium in Los Angeles will host eight matches, including three group stage fixtures, two Round of 32 clashes, and a highly anticipated Quarter-Final.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In addition to the Olympic games, California also hosts the California State Games.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Many sports, such as surfing, snowboarding, and skateboarding, were invented in California, while others like volleyball, beach soccer, and skiing were popularized in the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Other sports that are big in the state include golf, rodeo, tennis, mountain climbing, marathon running, horse racing, bowling, mixed martial arts, boxing, and motorsports, especially NASCAR and Formula One.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has the most school students in the country, with over 6.2 million in the 2005–06 school year, giving California more students in school than 36 states have in total population and one of the highest projected enrollments in the country.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Public secondary education consists of high schools that teach elective courses in trades, languages, and liberal arts with tracks for gifted, college-bound and industrial arts students.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's public educational system is supported by a unique constitutional amendment that requires a minimum annual funding level for grades K–12 and community colleges that grows with the economy and student enrollment figures.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2016, California's K–12 public school per-pupil spending was ranked 22nd in the nation ($11,500 per student vs. $11,800 for the U.S. average).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] For 2012, California's K–12 public schools ranked 48th in the number of employees per student, at 0.102 (the U.S. average was 0.137), while paying the 7th most per employee, $49,000 (the U.S. average was $39,000).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] , and the state's flagship public university.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] is a private university that is one of the top-ranked universities in the world.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has a particularly high density of arts colleges, including the California College of the Arts, California Institute of the Arts, San Francisco Art Institute, Art Center College of Design, and Academy of Art University, among others.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, California's gross state product (GSP) was $4.250 trillion, the largest of any U.S. state and the state's per capita personal income was $91,116.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California is responsible for one seventh of the nation's gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As of 2025, California's nominal GDP is larger than all but four countries.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In terms of purchasing power parity (PPP), it is larger than all but eight countries.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's economy is larger than Africa's and Australia's and is almost as large as South America's.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state recorded total, non-farm employment of 16,677,800 as of September 2021 among 966,224 employer establishments.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As of 2024, California is home to 57 of the *Fortune* 500 companies, the highest number of any U.S. state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2025, 465,101 businesses formed in California, the second highest in the country behind Florida.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As of 2025, 4.3 million small businesses were in the state, making up 99.8% of businesses, and employing 47.4% of the state's work force.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As the largest and second-largest U.S. ports respectively, the Port of Los Angeles and the Port of Long Beach in Southern California collectively play a pivotal role in the global supply chain, together hauling in about 40% of all imports to the U.S. by TEU volume.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Port of Oakland and Port of Hueneme are the 10th and 26th largest seaports in the U.S., respectively, by number of TEUs handled.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The five largest sectors of employment in California are trade, transportation, and utilities; government; professional and business services; education and health services; and leisure and hospitality.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In output, the five largest sectors are financial services, followed by trade, transportation, and utilities; education and health services; government; and manufacturing.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has an unemployment rate of 5.3% as of May 2025.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's economy is dependent on trade and international related commerce accounts for about one-quarter of the state's economy, and representing 7% of their GDP; California's biggest trade partner is Mexico.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2008, California exported $144 billion worth of goods, up from $134 billion in 2007 and $127 billion in 2006.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Vehicles, computers and electronic products are California's top exports, accounting for 42% of all the state's exports in 2008; over 50 car companies operate in California, such as Tesla and Mazda.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Agriculture is an important sector in California's economy.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Department of Agriculture, in 2011, the three largest California agricultural products by value were milk and cream, shelled almonds, and grapes.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Farming-related sales more than quadrupled over the past three decades, from $7.3 billion in 1974 to nearly $31 billion in 2004.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] This increase has occurred despite a 15% decline in acreage devoted to farming during the period, and water supply suffering from chronic instability.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Factors contributing to the growth in sales-per-acre include more intensive use of active farmlands and technological improvements in crop production.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2008, California's 81,500 farms and ranches generated $36.2 billion products revenue.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2011, that number grew to $43.5 billion products revenue.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The agriculture sector accounts for 2% of the state's GDP and employs around 3% of its total workforce.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Per capita GDP in 2021 was $85,546, ranking fourth in the nation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Per capita income varies widely by geographic region and profession.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Central Valley is the most impoverished, with migrant farm workers making less than minimum wage.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] According to a 2005 report by the Congressional Research Service, the San Joaquin Valley was characterized as one of the most economically depressed regions in the U.S., on par with the region of Appalachia.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Using the supplemental poverty measure, California has a poverty rate of 23.5%, the highest of any state in the country.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] However, using the official measure the poverty rate was only 13.3% as of 2017.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Many coastal cities include some of the wealthiest per-capita areas in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The high-technology sectors in Northern California, specifically Silicon Valley, in Santa Clara and San Mateo counties, have emerged from the economic downturn caused by the dot-com bust.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2019, there were 1,042,027 millionaire households in the state, more than any other state in the nation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2010, California residents were ranked first among the states with the best average credit score of 754.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] State spending increased from $56 billion in 1998 to $127 billion in 2011.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has the third highest per capita spending on welfare among the states, as well as the highest spending on welfare at $6.67 billion.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In January 2011, California's total debt was at least $265 billion.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] On June 27, 2013, Governor Jerry Brown signed a balanced budget (no deficit) for the state, its first in decades; however, the state's debt remains at $132 billion.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] While Proposition 30 also enacted a minimum state sales tax of 7.5%, this sales tax increase was not extended by Proposition 55 and reverted to a previous minimum state sales tax rate of 7.25% in 2017.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Local governments can and do levy additional sales taxes in addition to this minimum rate.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Property tax increases are capped at 2% annually or the rate of inflation (whichever is lower), per Proposition 13.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Because it is the most populous state in the U.S., California is one of the country's largest users of energy.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state has extensive hydro-electric energy generation facilities, however, moving water is the single largest energy use in the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Also, due to high energy rates, conservation mandates, mild weather in the largest population centers and strong environmental movement, its *per capita* energy use is one of the smallest of any state in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Due to the high electricity demand, California imports more electricity than any other state, primarily hydroelectric power from states in the Pacific Northwest (via Path 15 and Path 66) and coal- and natural gas-fired production from the desert Southwest via Path 46.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state's crude oil and natural gas deposits are located in the Central Valley and along the coast, including the large Midway-Sunset Oil Field.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Natural gas-fired power plants typically account for more than one-half of state electricity generation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As a result of the state's strong environmental movement, California has some of the most aggressive renewable energy goals in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Clean Energy, Jobs and Affordability Act of 2022 commits the state to running its operations on clean, renewable energy resources by 2035, and SB 1203 also requires the state to achieve net-zero operations for all agencies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Currently, several solar power plants such as the Solar Energy Generating Systems facility are located in the Mojave Desert.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's wind farms include Altamont Pass, San Gorgonio Pass, and Tehachapi Pass.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Tehachapi area is also where the Tehachapi Energy Storage Project is located.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Several dams across the state provide hydro-electric power.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] It would be possible to convert the total supply to 100% renewable energy, including heating, cooling and mobility, by 2050.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has one major nuclear power plant (Diablo Canyon) in operation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The San Onofre nuclear plant was shut down in 2013.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] More than 1,700 tons of radioactive waste are stored at San Onofre, and sit on the coast where there is a record of past tsunamis.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Voters banned the approval of new nuclear power plants since the late 1970s because of concerns over radioactive waste disposal.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Several cities such as Oakland, Berkeley and Davis have declared themselves as nuclear-free zones.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's vast terrain is connected by an extensive system of controlled-access highways ('freeways'), limited-access roads ('expressways'), and highways.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California is known for its car culture, giving California's cities a reputation for severe traffic congestion.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Construction and maintenance of state roads and statewide transportation planning are primarily the responsibility of the California Department of Transportation, nicknamed "Caltrans".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The rapidly growing population of the state is straining all of its transportation networks, and California has some of the worst roads in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Reason Foundation's 19th Annual Report on the Performance of State Highway Systems ranked California's highways the third-worst of any state, with Alaska second, and Rhode Island first.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state has been a pioneer in road construction.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] One of the state's more visible landmarks, the Golden Gate Bridge, was the longest suspension bridge main span in the world at 4,200 feet (1,300 m) between 1937 (when it opened) and 1964.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] With its orange paint and panoramic views of the bay, this highway bridge is a popular tourist attraction and also accommodates pedestrians and bicyclists.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge (often abbreviated the "Bay Bridge"), completed in 1936, transports about 280,000 vehicles per day on two-decks.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Its two sections meet at Yerba Buena Island through the world's largest diameter transportation bore tunnel, at 76 feet (23 m) wide by 58 feet (18 m) high.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Arroyo Seco Parkway, connecting Los Angeles and Pasadena, opened in 1940 as the first freeway in the Western U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] It was later extended south to the Four Level Interchange in downtown Los Angeles, regarded as the first stack interchange ever built.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The California Highway Patrol is the largest statewide police agency in the U.S. in employment with more than 10,000 employees.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] They are responsible for providing any police-sanctioned service to anyone on California's state-maintained highways and on state property.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Los Angeles International Airport (LAX), the 4th busiest airport in the world in 2018, and San Francisco International Airport (SFO), the 25th busiest airport in the world in 2018, are major hubs for trans-Pacific and transcontinental traffic.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] There are about a dozen important commercial airports and many more general aviation airports throughout the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Inter-city rail travel is provided by Amtrak California; the three routes, the *Capitol Corridor*, *Pacific Surfliner*, and *Gold Runner*, are funded by Caltrans.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] These services are the busiest intercity rail lines in the U.S. outside the Northeast Corridor and ridership is continuing to set records.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The routes are becoming increasingly popular over flying, especially on the LAX-SFO route.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Integrated subway and light rail networks are found in Los Angeles (Los Angeles Metro Rail) and San Francisco (Muni Metro).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Light rail systems are also found in San Jose (VTA light rail), San Diego (San Diego Trolley), Sacramento (SacRT light rail), and Northern San Diego County (Sprinter).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Furthermore, commuter rail networks serve the San Francisco Bay Area (Altamont Corridor Express, Bay Area Rapid Transit, Caltrain, Sonoma–Marin Area Rail Transit), Greater Los Angeles (Metrolink), and San Diego County (Coaster).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The California High-Speed Rail Authority was authorized in 1996 by the state legislature to plan a California High-Speed Rail system to put before the voters.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The plan they devised, 2008 California Proposition 1A, connecting all the major population centers in the state, was approved by the voters at the November 2008 general election.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The first phase of construction was begun in 2015, and the first segment 171 miles (275 km) long, is planned to be put into operation by the end of 2030.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Planning and work on the rest of the system is continuing, with funding for completing it is an ongoing issue.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's 2023 integrated passenger rail master plan includes a high speed rail system.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Nearly all counties operate bus lines, and many cities operate their own city bus lines as well.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Intercity bus travel is provided by Greyhound, Megabus, and Amtrak Thruway.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's interconnected water system is the world's largest, managing over 40,000,000 acre-feet (49 km3) of water per year, centered on six main systems of aqueducts and infrastructure projects.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Water use and conservation in California is a politically divisive issue, as the state experiences periodic droughts and has to balance the demands of its large agricultural and urban sectors, especially in the arid southern portion of the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state's widespread redistribution of water also invites the frequent scorn of environmentalists.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The California Water Wars, a conflict between Los Angeles and the Owens Valley over water rights, is one of the most well-known examples of the struggle to secure adequate water supplies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The capital city of California is Sacramento.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state also allows ballot propositions: direct participation of the electorate by initiative, referendum, recall, and ratification.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Before the passage of Proposition 14 in 2010, California allowed each political party to choose whether to have a closed primary or a primary where only party members and independents vote.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] After June 8, 2010, when Proposition 14 was approved, excepting only the U.S. president and county central committee offices, all candidates in the primary elections are listed on the ballot with their preferred party affiliation, but they are not the official nominee of that party.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] At the primary election, the two candidates with the top votes will advance to the general election regardless of party affiliation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] This is known as a nonpartisan blanket primary.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] If at a special primary election, one candidate receives more than 50% of all the votes cast, they are elected to fill the vacancy and no special general election will be held.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The California executive branch consists of the governor and seven other elected constitutional officers: lieutenant governor, attorney general, secretary of state, state controller, state treasurer, insurance commissioner, and state superintendent of public instruction.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] They serve four-year terms and may be re-elected only once.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The many California state agencies that are under the governor's cabinet are grouped together to form cabinet-level entities that are referred to by government officials as "superagencies".
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Those departments that are directly under the other independently elected officers work separately from these superagencies.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The California State Legislature consists of a 40-member Senate and 80-member Assembly.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Senators serve four-year terms and Assembly members two.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Members of the Assembly are subject to term limits of six terms, and members of the Senate are subject to term limits of three terms.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's legal system is explicitly based upon English common law but carries many features from Spanish civil law, such as community property.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Capital punishment is a legal form of punishment and the state has the largest "Death Row" population in the country (though Oklahoma and Texas are far more active in carrying out executions).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has performed 13 executions since 1976, with the last being in 2006.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's judiciary system is the largest in the U.S. with a total of 1,600 judges (the federal system has only about 840).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] At the apex is the seven-member Supreme Court of California, while the California Courts of Appeal serve as the primary appellate courts and the California Superior Courts serve as the primary trial courts.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Justices of the Supreme Court and Courts of Appeal are appointed by the governor, but are subject to retention by the electorate every 12 years.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The administration of the state's court system is controlled by the Judicial Council, composed of the chief justice of the California Supreme Court, 14 judicial officers, four representatives from the State Bar of California, and one member from each house of the state legislature.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In fiscal year 2020–2021, the state judiciary's 2,000 judicial officers and 18,000 judicial branch employees processed approximately 4.4 million cases.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has an extensive system of local government that manages public functions throughout the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Like most states, California is divided into counties, of which there are 58 (including San Francisco) covering the entire state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Most urbanized areas are incorporated as cities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] School districts, which are independent of cities and counties, handle public education.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Many other functions, such as fire protection and water supply, especially in unincorporated areas, are handled by special districts.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Per Article 11, Section 1, of the Constitution of California, they are the legal subdivisions of the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In addition, the county serves as the local government for all unincorporated areas.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Each county is governed by an elected board of supervisors.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Incorporated cities and towns in California are either charter or general-law municipalities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] General-law municipalities owe their existence to state law and are consequently governed by it; charter municipalities are governed by their own city or town charters.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Municipalities incorporated in the 19th century tend to be charter municipalities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] All ten of the state's most populous cities are charter cities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Most small cities have a council–manager form of government, where the elected city council appoints a city manager to supervise the operations of the city.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Some larger cities have a directly elected mayor who oversees the city government.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In many council-manager cities, the city council selects one of its members as a mayor, sometimes rotating through the council membership—but this type of mayoral position is primarily ceremonial.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Government of San Francisco is the only consolidated city-county in California, where both the city and county governments have been merged into one unified jurisdiction.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] About 1,102 school districts, independent of cities and counties, handle California's public education.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California school districts may be organized as elementary districts, high school districts, unified school districts combining elementary and high school grades, or community college districts.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] There are about 3,400 special districts in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] A special district, defined by California Government Code § 16271(d) as "any agency of the state for the local performance of governmental or proprietary functions within limited boundaries", provides a limited range of services within a defined geographic area.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The geographic area of a special district can spread across multiple cities or counties, or could consist of only a portion of one.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Most of California's special districts are *single-purpose districts*, and provide one service.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state of California sends 52 members to the House of Representatives, the nation's largest congressional state delegation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Consequently, California also has the largest number of electoral votes in national presidential elections, with 54.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The former speaker of the House of Representatives is the representative of California's 20th district, Kevin McCarthy.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In response to the 2025 Texas redistricting, Governor Newsom secured legislative approval of California Proposition 50 in August 2025, which would redraw the state's congressional districts.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The proposition was approved by 64.4% of voters, adding as many as five seats for the Democratic Party for the 2026 midterms.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Department of Defense had a total of 117,806 active duty servicemembers of which 88,370 were Sailors or Marines, 18,339 were Airmen, and 11,097 were Soldiers, with 61,365 Department of Defense civilian employees.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Additionally, there were a total of 57,792 Reservists and Guardsman in California.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2010, Los Angeles County was the largest origin of military recruits in the U.S. by county, with 1,437 individuals enlisting in the military.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] However, as of 2002, Californians were relatively under-represented in the military as a proportion to its population.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2000, California, had 2,569,340 veterans of U.S. military service.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As of 2010, there were 1,942,775 veterans living in California, of which 1,457,875 served during a period of armed conflict, and just over four thousand served before World War II (the largest population of this group of any state).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California's military forces consist of the Army and Air National Guard, the naval and state military reserve (militia), and the California Cadet Corps.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has an idiosyncratic political culture compared to the rest of the country, and is sometimes regarded as a trendsetter.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In socio-cultural mores and national politics, Californians are perceived as more liberal than other Americans, especially those who live in the inland states.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In the 2016 U.S. presidential election, California had the third highest percentage of Democratic votes behind the District of Columbia and Hawaii.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In the 2020 U.S. presidential election, it had the 6th highest behind D.C., Vermont, Massachusetts, Maryland, and Hawaii.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] According to the Cook Political Report, California contains five of the 15 most Democratic congressional districts in the U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California was the second state to recall their state governor, the second state to legalize abortion, and the only state to ban marriage for gay couples twice by vote (including Proposition 8 in 2008).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Voters also passed Proposition 71 in 2004 to fund stem cell research, making California the second state to legalize stem cell research, and Proposition 14 in 2010 to completely change the state's primary election process.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California has also experienced disputes over water rights; and a tax revolt, culminating with the passage of Proposition 13 in 1978, limiting state property taxes.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California voters have rejected affirmative action on multiple occasions, most recently in November 2020.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The state's trend towards the Democratic Party and away from the Republican Party can be seen in state elections.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] From 1899 to 1939, California had exclusively Republican governors.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Several political movements have advocated for California independence.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The California National Party and the California Freedom Coalition both advocate for California independence along the lines of progressivism and civic nationalism.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Yes California movement attempted to organize an independence referendum via ballot initiative for 2019, which was then postponed.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] The Democrats also hold a supermajority in both houses of the state legislature.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] There are 62 Democrats and 18 Republicans in the Assembly; and 32 Democrats and eight Republicans in the Senate.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] From 1952 through 1988, California was a Republican-leaning state, as the party carried the state's electoral votes in nine of ten elections, with 1964 as the sole exception.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Southern California Republicans Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan were both elected twice as the 37th and 40th U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] However, Democrats have won all of California's electoral votes for the last eight elections, starting in 1992.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] House, the Democrats held a 34–19 edge in the California delegation of the 110th U.S.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] As the result of gerrymandering, the districts in California were usually dominated by one or the other party, and few districts were considered competitive.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In 2008, Californians passed Proposition 20 to empower a 14-member independent citizen commission to redraw districts for both local politicians and Congress.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] After the 2012 elections, when the new system took effect, Democrats gained four seats and held a 38–15 majority in the delegation.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Following the 2018 midterm House elections, Democrats won 46 out of 53 congressional house seats in California, leaving Republicans with seven.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In general, Democratic strength is centered in the populous coastal regions of the Los Angeles metropolitan area and the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Republican strength is still greatest in eastern parts of the state.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Orange County had remained largely Republican until the 2016 and 2018 elections, in which a majority of the county's votes were cast for Democratic candidates.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] One study ranked Berkeley, Oakland, Inglewood and San Francisco in the top 20 most liberal American cities; and Bakersfield, Orange, Escondido, Garden Grove, and Simi Valley in the top 20 most conservative cities.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] In October 2022, out of the 26,876,800 people eligible to vote, 21,940,274 people were registered to vote.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] Of the people registered, the three largest registered groups were Democrats (10,283,258), Republicans (5,232,094), and No Party Preference (4,943,696).
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California retains the death penalty, though it has not been used since 2006.
[src:antarctica-novel/california-p03] California is a member of the Commission of the Californias, a tri-lateral forum for cooperation between the U.S. state of California and the Mexican states of Baja California and Baja California Sur.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] As of December 2023, CNN had 68,974,000 television households as subscribers in the United States.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] According to Nielsen, down from 80 million in March 2021.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] In June 2021, CNN ranked third in viewership among cable news networks, behind Fox News and MS NOW (formerly MSNBC), averaging 580,000 viewers throughout the day, down 49% from a year earlier, amid sharp declines in viewers across all cable news networks.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] Globally, CNN programming has aired through CNN International, seen by viewers in over 212 countries and territories.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] Since May 2019, however, the American domestic version has absorbed international news coverage in order to reduce programming costs.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] The American version, sometimes referred to as CNN (US), is also available in Canada, and some islands in the Caribbean.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] CNN also licenses its brand and content to other channels, such as CNN-News18 in India.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] In Japan it broadcasts CNNj which started in 2003, with simultaneous translation in Japanese.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] CNN has often been subjected to criticism from conservative media and other organizations for having a perceived left-wing bias; conversely, it has also been criticized for perceived false balance in support of conservative positions.
[src:antarctica-novel/cnn] The Cable News Network launched at 5:00 p.m.
